{"title_page": "Catcliffe railway station", "text_new": "{{Short description|Disused railway station in South Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n|name        = Catcliffe\n|locale      = [[Catcliffe]]\n|borough     = [[Metropolitan Borough of Rotherham|Rotherham]]\n|original    = [[Sheffield District Railway]]\n|pregroup    = [[Great Central Railway]]\n|postgroup   = [[London and North Eastern Railway]]\n|platforms   = 2\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.392137|-1.364254|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n|gridref     = SK423885\n|years       = 30 May 1900\n|events      = Opened\n|years1      = 11 September 1939\n|events1     = Closed\n|years2      = 6 October 1946\n|events2     = Reopened\n|years3      = 17 March 1947\n|events3     = Closed{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=56}}\n}}\n{{Lancashire, Derbyshire & East Coast Railway|collapse=yes}}\n[[File:Shefdist.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Sheffield District Railway and connecting lines]]\n{{Sheffield District Railway|collapse=yes}}\n'''Catcliffe railway station''' is a former [[Train station|railway station]] in the [[Catcliffe]] area of [[Rotherham]], [[South Yorkshire]], England.\n\n==History==\nThe station was located on the [[Sheffield District Railway]], just over {{convert|1|mi|km}} north of its junction with the [[North Midland Railway]] line at [[Treeton]] Junction. \n\nThe line was carried on a 9-arch brick-built [[viaduct]] over the [[River Rother, South Yorkshire|Rother Valley]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.treetonweb.co.uk/parish/viaductcatcliffe.htm# |title=Catcliffe Viaduct: via ''treetonweb'' |access-date=16 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220025210/http://www.treetonweb.co.uk/parish/viaductcatcliffe.htm# |archive-date=20 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2808584 Catcliffe Viaduct(1): via ''geograph'']</ref><ref>[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/3466246 Catcliffe Viaduct(2): via ''geograph'']</ref> The station was constructed at the northern end of this, near to the village. The station was noted for its bleak and isolated location which earned it the name \"Klondyke\" from the local population.{{sfn|Dow|1965|p=170}} Both station and platforms were built of wood. The awnings were of the distinctive [[Lancashire, Derbyshire and East Coast Railway|LD&ECR]] style.{{sfn|Pixton|2001|p=87}}{{sfn|Booth|2013|p=56}} The platforms and their supports closely resembled those at [[Boughton (Nottinghamshire) railway station|Boughton]] and [[Dukeries Junction railway station|Dukeries Junction]].\n\nThe station was opened on 30 April 1900{{sfn|Dow|1965|p=170}} and closed on 11 September 1939. It was briefly reopened from 6 October 1946 to 17 March 1947.{{sfn|Cupit|Taylor|1984|p=42}}\n\n==Former passenger services==\nThere never was a Sunday service from Catcliffe.\n\nIn 1922 two passenger services served Catcliffe:\n\n*From Sheffield to Mansfield via Langwith Junction, and\n*From Sheffield to Chesterfield via the \"Old Road\".\n\nThe Sheffield to Mansfield service consisted of three trains per day each way between the MR station at Sheffield and the MR station at [[Mansfield railway station (England)|Mansfield]] calling at [[Attercliffe Road railway station|Attercliffe Road]], [[West Tinsley railway station|West Tinsley]], '''Catcliffe''', [[Treeton railway station|Treeton]], [[Woodhouse Mill railway station|Woodhouse Mill]], the LD&ECR \"Beighton Branch\" to [[Shirebrook North railway station|Langwith Junction (later renamed Shirebrook North)]], the MR station at [[Shirebrook railway station|Shirebrook (later renamed Shirebrook West)]], [[Mansfield Woodhouse railway station|Mansfield Woodhouse]] and Mansfield, taking about an hour and a quarter. On Saturdays an extra lunchtime train ran out and back, calling at Catcliffe northbound only.\n\nTo travel from Sheffield (MR) to Chesterfield (MR) via the \"Old Road\" it was necessary to head off north east towards Rotherham then swing south onto the \"Old Road\" itself which was the original [[North Midland Railway]] route from Rotherham to Chesterfield along the Rother Valley. Three trains a day ran to [[Holmes railway station|Holmes]] almost in Rotherham itself before turning sharply south to Treeton. Three trains plus an extra on Saturdays turned off before [[Brightside railway station|Brightside]] onto Sheffield District Railway metals to Treeton, however, only one of these called at Catcliffe plus one on Saturdays, the others passed without stopping.{{sfn|Bradshaw|1985|p=718}}\n\nBy August 1939 the service to Mansfield remained little changed, except that Upperthorpe and Killamarsh station had closed in 1930 and not all called at Attercliffe Road.\n\nThe Sheffield to Chesterfield service via Catcliffe and the Old Road had evolved to two trains per day with an extra on Saturdays, all of which called at Catcliffe.<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/16418497@N03/6234644598/in/photostream/ Bradshaw, August 1939 p903]</ref> \n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line\n|previous=[[West Tinsley railway station|West Tinsley]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> \n|next=[[Treeton railway station|Treeton]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> \n|route=[[London and North Eastern Railway]]<br /><small>[[Sheffield District Railway]]</small>\n|col={{LNER colour}}\n}}\n{{rail end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last=Booth |first=Chris |title=The Lancashire, Derbyshire and East Coast Railway A pictorial view of the \"Dukeries Route\" and branches|year=2013 |publisher=Blurb |location= |isbn=978-1-78155-660-3 |id=06715029 |ref=harv }}\n*{{Bradshaw-1922July}}\n*{{Butt-Stations}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Cupit |first1=J. |last2=Taylor |first2=W. |title=The Lancashire, Derbyshire & East Coast Railway |edition=2nd |series=Oakwood Library of Railway History |year=1984 |origyear=1966 |publisher=Oakwood Press |location=[[Headington]] |isbn=978-0-85361-302-2 |id=OL19 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Dow-GC3}}\n*{{cite book |last=Pixton |first=Bob |title=North Midland: Portrait of a Famous Route: Part 2 Chesterfield-Sheffield-Rotherham |year=2001 |publisher=Runpast Publishing, (now Book Law) |location=[[Nottingham]]|isbn=978-1-870754-51-4 |ref=harv }}\n{{refend}}\n==External links==\n* [http://www.npemap.org.uk/tiles/map.html#440,389,1 Catcliffe station on an old OS map] ''npe Maps''\n* [http://www.RailMapOnline.com/UKIEMap.php?lat=53.39213&lng=-1.36438&zoom=13 The station and line on multiple overlain maps] ''Rail Map Online''\n* [http://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=16&lat=53.3927&lon=-1.3624&layers=6&b=1 The station on old OS maps] ''National Library of Scotland''\n* [http://www.railwaycodes.org.uk/elrs/_mileages/B/BTJ.txt The station and line BTJ, with mileages] ''Railway Codes''\n* [http://signalboxes.com/catcliffe-signalbox-and-station.php Catcliffe station] ''signalboxes''\n\n[[Category:Disused railway stations in Rotherham]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1900]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1939]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1946]]\n[[Category:Railway stations closed in 1947]]\n[[Category:Former Great Central Railway stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Disused railway station in South Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2017}}\n{{Infobox UK disused station\n|name        = Catcliffe\n|locale      = [[Catcliffe]]\n|borough     = [[Metropolitan Borough of Rotherham|Rotherham]]\n|original    = [[Sheffield District Railway]]\n|pregroup    = [[Great Central Railway]]\n|postgroup   = [[London and North Eastern Railway]]\n|platforms   = 2\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.392137|-1.364254|type:railwaystation_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n|gridref     = SK423885\n|years       = 30 May 1900\n|events      = Opened\n|years1      = 11 September 1939\n|events1     = Closed\n|years2      = 6 October 1946\n|events2     = Reopened\n|years3      = 17 March 1947\n|events3     = Closed{{sfn|Butt|1995|p=56}}\n}}\n{{Lancashire, Derbyshire & East Coast Railway|collapse=yes}}\n[[File:Shefdist.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Sheffield District Railway and connecting lines]]\n{{Sheffield District Railway|collapse=yes}}\n'''Catcliffe railway station''' is a former [[Train station|railway station]] in the [[Catcliffe]] area of [[Rotherham]], [[South Yorkshire]], England.\n\n==History==\nThe station was located on the [[Sheffield District Railway]], just over {{convert|1|mi|km}} north of its junction with the [[North Midland Railway]] line at [[Treeton]] Junction. \n\nThe line was carried on a 9-arch brick-built [[viaduct]] over the [[River Rother, South Yorkshire|Rother Valley]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.treetonweb.co.uk/parish/viaductcatcliffe.htm# |title=Catcliffe Viaduct: via ''treetonweb'' |access-date=16 June 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220025210/http://www.treetonweb.co.uk/parish/viaductcatcliffe.htm# |archive-date=20 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/2808584 Catcliffe Viaduct(1): via ''geograph'']</ref><ref>[https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/3466246 Catcliffe Viaduct(2): via ''geograph'']</ref> The station was constructed at the northern end of this, near to the village. The station was noted for its bleak and isolated location which earned it the name \"Klondyke\" from the local population.{{sfn|Dow|1965|p=170}} Both station and platforms were built of wood. The awnings were of the distinctive [[Lancashire, Derbyshire and East Coast Railway|LD&ECR]] style.{{sfn|Pixton|2001|p=87}}{{sfn|Booth|2013|p=56}} The platforms and their supports closely resembled those at [[Boughton (Nottinghamshire) railway station|Boughton]] and [[Dukeries Junction railway station|Dukeries Junction]].\n\nThe station was opened on 30 April 1900{{sfn|Dow|1965|p=170}} and closed on 11 September 1939. It was briefly reopened from 6 October 1946 to 17 March 1947.{{sfn|Cupit|Taylor|1984|p=42}}\n\n==Former passenger services==\nThere never was a Sunday service from Catcliffe.\n\nIn 1922 two passenger services served Catcliffe:\n\n*From Sheffield to Mansfield via Langwith Junction, and\n*From Sheffield to Chesterfield via the \"Old Road\".\n\nThe Sheffield to Mansfield service consisted of three trains per day each way between the MR station at Sheffield and the MR station at [[Mansfield railway station (England)|Mansfield]] calling at [[Attercliffe Road railway station|Attercliffe Road]], [[West Tinsley railway station|West Tinsley]], '''Catcliffe''', [[Treeton railway station|Treeton]], [[Woodhouse Mill railway station|Woodhouse Mill]], the LD&ECR \"Beighton Branch\" to [[Shirebrook North railway station|Langwith Junction (later renamed Shirebrook North)]], the MR station at [[Shirebrook railway station|Shirebrook (later renamed Shirebrook West)]], [[Mansfield Woodhouse railway station|Mansfield Woodhouse]] and Mansfield, taking about an hour and a quarter. On Saturdays an extra lunchtime train ran out and back, calling at Catcliffe northbound only.\n\nTo travel from Sheffield (MR) to Chesterfield (MR) via the \"Old Road\" it was necessary to head off north east towards Rotherham then swing south onto the \"Old Road\" itself which was the original [[North Midland Railway]] route from Rotherham to Chesterfield along the Rother Valley. Three trains a day ran to [[Holmes railway station|Holmes]] almost in Rotherham itself before turning sharply south to Treeton. Three trains plus an extra on Saturdays turned off before [[Brightside railway station|Brightside]] onto Sheffield District Railway metals to Treeton, however, only one of these called at Catcliffe plus one on Saturdays, the others passed without stopping.{{sfn|Bradshaw|1985|p=718}}\n\nBy August 1939 the service to Mansfield remained little changed, except that Upperthorpe and Killamarsh station had closed in 1930 and not all called at Attercliffe Road.\n\nThe Sheffield to Chesterfield service via Catcliffe and the Old Road had evolved to two trains per day with an extra on Saturdays, all of which called at Catcliffe.<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/16418497@N03/6234644598/in/photostream/ Bradshaw, August 1939 p903]</ref> \n\n{{Disused Rail Start}}\n{{Rail line\n|previous=[[West Tinsley railway station|West Tinsley]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> \n|next=[[Treeton railway station|Treeton]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> \n|route=[[London and North Eastern Railway]]<br /><small>[[Sheffield District Railway]]</small>\n|col={{LNER colour}}\n}}\n{{rail end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|35em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last=Booth |first=Chris |title=The Lancashire, Derbyshire and East Coast Railway A pictorial view of the \"Dukeries Route\" and branches|year=2013 |publisher=Blurb |location= |isbn=978-1-78155-660-3 |id=06715029 |ref=harv }}\n*{{Butt-Stations}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Cupit |first1=J. |last2=Taylor |first2=W. |title=The Lancashire, Derbyshire & East Coast Railway |edition=2nd |series=Oakwood Library of Railway History |year=1984 |origyear=1966 |publisher=Oakwood Press |location=[[Headington]] |isbn=978-0-85361-302-2 |id=OL19 |ref=harv}}\n*{{Dow-GC3}}\n*{{cite book |last=Pixton |first=Bob |title=North Midland: Portrait of a Famous Route: Part 2 Chesterfield-Sheffield-Rotherham |year=2001 |publisher=Runpast Publishing, (now Book Law) |location=[[Nottingham]]|isbn=978-1-870754-51-4 |ref=harv }}\n{{refend}}\n==External links==\n* [http://www.npemap.org.uk/tiles/map.html#440,389,1 Catcliffe station on an old OS map] ''npe Maps''\n* [http://www.RailMapOnline.com/UKIEMap.php?lat=53.39213&lng=-1.36438&zoom=13 The station and line on multiple overlain maps] ''Rail Map Online''\n* [http://maps.nls.uk/geo/explore/#zoom=16&lat=53.3927&lon=-1.3624&layers=6&b=1 The station on old OS maps] ''National Library of Scotland''\n* [http://ww