registration_plate      = KA-\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Bidarakote''' is a village in the [[Mandya district]] of the Indian state of [[Karnataka]].  It is 20&nbsp;km away from its district headquarters [[Mandya]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mandya.nic.in |title=Welcome to Mandya District |publisher=Mandya.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2012-11-14}}</ref><ref>[http://www.karnatakatourism.com ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917233758/http://www.karnatakatourism.com/ |date=17 September 2009  }}</ref>\n\nBidarakote was founded before 1300. The statue of Varadaraja swamy at the centre of the village, resembles Udupi Sri Krishna of Udupi. The Sri Someshwara Temple was built by [[Chola dynasty]].\n\nRecently{{when?|date=October 2018}} 12 sacred [[Lingam|Jyotirlingam]] were established at Sri Someshwara by Mr Nagaraju.And Parvathi vigraha and subramanya vigraha was established in someshwara temple by Krishnamurthy and family\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Mandya district]]\n\n\n{{Mandya-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2018}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{external links|date=November 2012}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2013}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Bidarakote\n| native_name             = Bidarkote\n| native_name_lang        = \n| other_name              = \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = village\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = <!--India Karnataka-->\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in Karnataka, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|12|50|48.81|N|76|55|44.45|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Karnataka]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Mandya district|Mandya]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = \n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = \n| population_as_of        = \n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Kannada]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code             = \n| registration_plate      = KA-\n| website                 = \n| footnotes               = \n}}\n\n'''Bidarakote''' is a village in the [[Mandya district]] of the Indian state of [[Karnataka]].  It is 20&nbsp;km away from its district headquarters [[Mandya]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mandya.nic.in |title=Welcome to Mandya District |publisher=Mandya.nic.in |date= |accessdate=2012-11-14}}</ref><ref>[http://www.karnatakatourism.com ]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917233758/http://www.karnatakatourism.com/ |date=17 September 2009  }}</ref>\n\nBidarakote was founded before 1300. The statue of Varadaraja swamy at the centre of the village, resembles Udupi Sri Krishna of Udupi. The Sri Someshwara Temple was built by [[Chola dynasty]].\n\nRecently{{when?|date=October 2018}} 12 sacred [[Lingam|Jyotirlingam]] were established at Sri Someshwara by Mr Nagaraju.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Mandya district]]\n\n\n{{Mandya-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "157.49.220.36", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bidarakote"}
{"title_page": "Arun Govil", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian actor}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Pakistan English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Arun Govil\n| image = ArunGovil.jpg\n| caption =Govil in 2009\n| birth_name  = Arun Govil\n| birth_date = 30 October<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/birthday-wishes-amit-navina-yash-and-arun|title=Birthday wishes for Amit, Navina, Yash and Arun|date=2012-10-30|website= Tellychakkar Dot Com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Meerut]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| nationality =  Indian\n| alma_mater   = [[Chaudhary Charan Singh University]]\n| occupation = {{hlist|Actor|producer}}\n| years_active       = 1977- Present\n| known_for          = [[Rama]] in<br>[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan (1987)]]\n| spouse = Shrilekha Govil\n| children = 2\n| relatives =[[Tabassum (actress)|Tabassum]] (sister-in-law)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rediff.com/movies/report/i-never-became-a-big-heroine-tabassum/20141029.htm|title=Nargis, Meena Kumari, Madhubala, Suraiya... they all loved me|website=www.rediff.com|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n}}\n'''Arun Govil''' is an [[India]]n actor and producer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tellychakkar.com/tv/tv-news/birthday-wishes-amit-navina-yash-and-arun|title=Birthday wishes for Amit, Navina, Yash and Arun|date=2012-10-30|website= Tellychakkar Dot Com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/people/arun-govil-10221|title=Arun Govil movies, filmography, biography and songs - Cinestaan.com|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodmdb.com/celebrities/arun-govil/6141|title=Arun Govil - BollywoodMDB|website=www.bollywoodmdb.com|language=en|access-date=2018-04-01}}</ref> He has acted in [[Hindi]], [[Bhojpuri]], [[Braj Bhasha]], [[Odia language|Odia]] and [[Telugu language|Telugu]] films. He is best known for playing Lord [[Rama]] in [[Ramanand Sagar]]'s hit television series ''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'' (1987).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://m.timesofindia.com/tv/news/hindi/I-would-never-regret-playing-lord-Ram-Arun-Govil/articleshow/17609352.cms|title=I would never regret playing lord Ram: Arun Govil - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/brunch/arun-govil-the-first-ram/story-iKYVwcBwMKdhiw6mfY3o3O.html|title=Arun Govil: the first Ram|date=2014-10-18|website=www.hindustantimes.com|access-date=2018-11-10|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.friendsofprasarbharati.org/2014/july/J26.htm|title=Recent news|website=www.friendsofprasarbharati.org|access-date=2018-11-10}}</ref>\nHe made his [[Bollywood]] debut in  [[Prashanta Nanda]]'s ''[[Paheli (1977 film)|Paheli]]'' (1977).<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/paheli-4741|title=Paheli (1977) - Review, Star Cast, News, Photos {{!}} Cinestaan|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-11-10}}</ref> He shot to stardom after he was cast in Kanak Mishra's ''[[Sawan Ko Aane Do]]'' (1979) and Satyen Bose's ''[[Saanch Ko Aanch Nahin]]'' (1979).<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/sawan-ko-aane-do-5029|title=Sawan Ko Aane Do (1979) - Review, Star Cast, News, Photos {{!}} Cinestaan|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-11-10}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/saanch-ko-aanch-nahin-4962|title=Saanch Ko Aanch Nahin (1979) - Review, Star Cast, News, Photos {{!}} Cinestaan|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-11-10}}</ref> He made his small screen debut in [[Ramanand Sagar]]'s ''[[Vikram Aur Betaal]]'' (1985).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/tv/vikram-aur-betaal-it-was-great-storytelling-with-a-twist/story-0oiq7ZcvrkkgQqNFJMi0FN.html|title=Vikram Aur Betaal: It was great storytelling with a twist|date=2016-05-12|website=www.hindustantimes.com|access-date=2018-11-10|language=en}}</ref> He was then cast as Lord [[Rama]] in [[Ramanand Sagar|Sagar]]'s  TV series ''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'' (1986), for which he won the Uptron Award in the Best Actor in a Leading Role category in 1988.<ref name=\":0\" /> He reprised his role as [[Rama]] in [[Ramanand Sagar|Sagar]]'s ''[[Luv Kush]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PL4E0DC6FA3D54BCBA|title=Luv Kush, Uttar Ramayan episodes|website=www.youtube.com|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref> \n\nHis role as [[Rama]] provided him great exposure and led him to be cast in other roles such as [[Harishchandra]] in the TV series ''Vishwamitra'' or [[Gautama Buddha|Buddha]] in the TV series ''Buddha''. He lent his voice as [[Rama]] in [[Yugo Sako]]'s Indo-Japanese animation film ''[[Ramayana: The Legend of Prince Rama]]'' (1992).<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/ramayana-the-legend-of-prince-rama-37637|title=Ramayana: The Legend of Prince Rama  (Released) - Review, Star Cast, News, Photos {{!}} Cinestaan|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref> He was panned for switching over to the role of [[Laxman]] in [[V. Madhusudhan Rao]]'s ''[[Lav Kush]]'' (1997).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/lav-kush-8148|title=Lav Kush (1997) - Review, Star Cast, News, Photos {{!}} Cinestaan|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nArun Govil was born in [[Meerut]], [[Uttar Pradesh]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.pagalparrot.com/arun-govil-daughter-sonika-govil/|title=Remember Arun Govil Who Played Ram In The First Ever 'Ramayana'? His Daughter Is All Grown Up Now!|date=2018-01-16|work=PagalParrot|access-date=2018-11-11|language=en-US}}</ref> He got his formal education at [[Chaudhary Charan Singh University]], [[Meerut]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], where he studied engineering science and acted in some plays.<ref name=\":2\" /> He spent his teenage life in [[Shahjahanpur]], [[Uttar Pradesh]]. His father wanted him to become a government servant while Arun wanted to do something for which he would be remembered.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Career==\nIn 1975, at the young age of 17 he moved to [[Mumbai]] to join his brother's business there. After a short while, he found that he no longer enjoyed the work and decided to find something more enjoyable.<ref name=\":0\" /> After doing dramas in college he decided to start acting. Govil got his first break in [[Indian cinema]] in the 1977 film ''[[Paheli]]'', when he was introduced to [[Tarachand Barjatya]] by his sister-in-law [[Tabassum (actress)|Tabassum]].<ref name=\":3\" /> Barjatya was really impressed by Govil's performance in the film and he signed him a three-film-deal \u2014 Kanak Mishra's ''[[Sawan Ko Aane Do]]'' (1979), Vijay Kapoor's ''[[Raadha Aur Seeta]]'' (1979) and Satyen Bose's ''[[Saanch Ko Aanch Nahin]]'' (1979). ''[[Sawan Ko Aane Do]]'' became a major success at box office catapulting Govil to stardom.<ref name=\":4\" /> ''[[Raadha Aur Seeta]]'' was a box office failure while ''[[Saanch Ko Aanch Nahin]]'' was another success at box office.<ref name=\":6\" /> He featured in Kanak Mishra's ''[[Jiyo To Aise Jiyo]]'' (1981) which was the 30th biggest hit of that year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/list/ls000028872/|title=Highest Grossing Hindi Movies of 1981|website=www.imdb.com|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref>\n\n[[Ramanand Sagar]] cast Govil as [[Vikramaditya]] in his television series ''[[Vikram Aur Betaal]]'' and [[Rama]] in his highly successful television series ''[[Ramayan (1987 TV series)|Ramayan]]'', for which he won the Uptron Award for \"Best Actor in a Leading Role\" in 1988.\n{{quote box\n|author = \u2014 Govil on his portrayal of [[Rama]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/articles/2018/jan/12/10381/arun-govil-aka-ram-people-touch-my-feet-even-30-years-after-ramayan|title=Arun Govil aka Ram: People touch my feet even 30 years after Ramayan|last=|first=|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-11-10}}</ref>\n|quote = \"When I came to know they are making ''Ramayan'', I said I would like to play Ram. It came to my mind that I should play that character. But I didn't say that because I thought it would be great for my career. The project was such that I felt like doing it. But it proved to be a very important milestone in my career and life. People still know me as Ram. Even in places like airport, they touch my feet. It's been happening since more than 30 years. It is still stuck in people's minds. Not only the older generation, but also the new generation has seen it. It has gone into the history of not only Indian television, but also the Indian psyche.\"\n|bgcolor = #edf3ee\n|align = right\n|salign = right\n                                       \n\n|width = 16em\n}}\nHis role as [[Rama]] provided great exposure to him and led to him being cast in other religious-based roles, including [[Harishchandra]] in ''Vishwamitra (TV series)'' and Buddha in TV series ''Buddha''. Arun Govil has worked in movies of several languages. He has worked in [[Oriya language|Oriya]] movies like ''Bidhira Bidhan'' (1989) and many [[Telugu language|Telugu]] movies like ''Edu Kondalaswamy'' (1991), ''Govindha Govindha'' (1993), ''The Great Robbery'' (1996) and ''Aa re Kaaliya''. He has also got an opportunity to anchor a show on lord Ram, ''Jahan Jahan Ram Charan Chali Jaahi''. He also lent his voice in 1992 mythological Indo-Japanese animation movie ''[[Ramayana: The Legend of Prince Rama]]'' as Lord [[Rama]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nHe later set up a production company with his ''Ramayan'' co-star [[Sunil Lahiri]]. He produced and acted in ''Mashaal'', a TV series based on the Indian independence movement. His wife Shrilekha acted and co-produced the show as well.\nRecently he appeared on Season 2 of The Kapil Sharma Show along with ramayan co stars Dipika Chikalia and Sunil Lahri.\n\n==Personal life==\nArun's father, Shri Chandra Prakash Govil, was a government officer. Arun is the fourth of six brothers and two sisters. His elder brother Vijay Govil is married to [[Tabassum (actress)|Tabassum]], a former child actress and the host of the first [[Bollywood]] Celebrity talk show on [[Doordarshan]]  ''[[Phool Khile Hain Gulshan Gulshan (TV series)|Phool Khile Hain Gulshan Gulshan]]'', which continued for 21 years. His nephew is Film and TV actor Hoshang Govil (Son of Vijay and Tabassum Govil). Govil is married to actress Shrilekha, with whom he has a son and a daughter.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Films===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year !! Film !! Character !! Notes\n|-\n|[[Bollywood films of 1977|1977]]\n|''[[Paheli (1977 film)|Paheli]]''\n|Balram\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Bollywood films of 1979|1979]]\n|''[[Sawan Ko Aane Do]]''\n|Birju\n|\n|-\n|''[[Saanch Ko Aanch Nahin]]''\n|Ajay S. Agarwal\n|\n|-\n|''[[Raadha Aur Seeta]]''\n|Shekhar Verma\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Bollywood films of 1980|1980]]\n|''[[Judaai (1980 film)|Judaai]]''\n|Umakant S. Verma\n|\n|-\n|''[[Ganga Dham]]''\n|Mohan\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"|[[Bollywood films of 1981|1981]]\n|''[[Jiyo To Aise Jiyo]]''\n|Kundan Sharma\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/jiyo-to-aise-jiyo-5342/cast-crew|title=Jiyo To Aise Jiyo (1981)  Cast - Actor, Actress, Director, Producer, Music Director {{!}} Cinestaan|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bollywoodmdb.com/movies/jiyo-to-aise-jiyo/3240|website=www.bollywoodmdb.com|title=Jiyo To Aise Jiyo|access-date=2018-10-28}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Itni Si Baat''\n|Anand\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/itni-si-baat-5279|title=Itni Si Baat (1981) - Review, Star Cast, News, Photos {{!}} Cinestaan|website=Cinestaan|access-date=2018-11-11}}</ref>\n|-\n|''Shradhanjali''\n|Raju Kumar\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cinestaan.com/movies/shradhanjali-5233|title=Shradhanjali (1981) - Review, St