 [[Sushil Koirala]] || 249 || Lost\n|}\n\n'''2017 House of Representatives Election Jhapa-5'''<ref>{{cite news|title=Jhapa : Province 1 \u2013 Nepal Election Latest Updates and Result for Federal Parliament|url=https://election.ekantipur.com/pradesh-1/district-jhapa?lng=eng|accessdate=10 December 2017|publisher=The Kathmandu Post}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Party !! Candidate !! Votes !! Status\n|-\n| [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist)|CPN-UML]] || K.P. Sharma Oli || 57,139 || Elected\n|-\n| [[Nepali Congress]] || Khagendra Adhikari|| 28,297 || Lost\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Oli cabinet, 2018]]\n*[[Oli cabinet, 2015]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cpnuml.org  Official website of CPN UML]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jhala Nath Khanal]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist\u2013Leninist)|CPN (UML)]]|years=2014\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=''Party dissolved''}}\n{{s-bef|before=''New party formed''}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Leader of the [[Nepal Communist Party|Nepal Communist Party (NCP)]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sushil Koirala]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Prime Ministers of Nepal|Prime Minister of Nepal]]|years=2015\u20132016}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Pushpa Kamal Dahal]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Sher Bahadur Deuba]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Prime Ministers of Nepal|Prime Minister of Nepal]]|years=2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Prime Ministers of Nepal}}\n{{Current Socialist rulers}}\n{{Current SAARC Leaders}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Oli, Khadga Prasad}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Nepal (Marxist\u2013Leninist) (1998) politicians]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Nepal (Pushpa Lal) politicians]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist\u2013Leninist) politicians]]\n[[Category:Nepal Communist Party (NCP) politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Nepalese Constituent Assembly]]\n[[Category:Nepalese Hindus]]\n[[Category:Nepalese prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:People from Terhathum District]]\n[[Category:Prime ministers of Nepal]]\n[[Category:People from Province No. 1]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nepalese politician and current Prime minister of Nepal}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name =KP Sharma Oli  \n| birth_name = Khadga Prasad Sharma Oli\n| image =File:KP Sharma Oli.png\n| office1 = 38th <!--not the 41st, only the first time is counted, otherwise would have been 63rd--> [[Prime Minister of Nepal]]\n| president2 = [[Ram Baran Yadav]]<br/>[[Bidhya Devi Bhandari]]\n| term_start2 = 12 October 2015\n| term_end2 = 4 August 2016\n| predecessor2 = [[Sushil Koirala]]\n| successor2 = [[Pushpa Kamal Dahal]]\n| term_start1 = 15 February 2018\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Sher Bahadur Deuba]]\n| successor1 = \n| president1 = [[Bidhya Devi Bhandari]]\n| office3 = Chairman of the [[Nepal Communist Party|Nepal Communist Party (NCP)]]\n| term_start3 = 17 May 2018\n| term_end3 = \n| predecessor3 = Position established\n| successor3 = \n| office4 = [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Nepal)|Minister for Foreign Affairs]]\n| primeminister4 = [[Girija Prasad Koirala]]\n| term_start4 = 2006\n| term_end4 = 2007\n| predecessor4 = \n| successor4 = \n| office5 = [[Ministry of Home Affairs (Nepal)|Minister of Home Affairs]]\n| primeminister5 = [[Man Mohan Adhikari]]\n| monarch5          =   [[Birendra of Nepal|Birendra Bir Bikram Shah]]\n| term_start5 = 1994\n| term_end5 = 1995\n| predecessor5 = \n| successor5 = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1952|2|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Tehrathum District|Tehrathum,Jhapa]], [[Kingdom of Nepal|Nepal]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| citizenship = Nepali\n| nationality = Nepalese\n| spouse = Radhika Shakya\n| parents = Mohan Prasad Oli, Madhumaya Oli\n| residence = Baluwatar, Kathmandu\n| party = [[Nepal Communist Party|Nepal Communist Party (NCP)]]\n}}\n'''Khadga Prasad Sharma Oli (\u0915\u0947 \u092a\u0940 \u0913\u0932\u0940)''' ({{lang-ne|\u0916\u0921\u094d\u0917\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0938\u093e\u0926 \u0913\u0932\u0940}}, {{IPA-ne|k\u02b0\u028c\u0256\u0261\u0259\u02c8pr\u0259\u02ccs\u0251\u02d0\u00f0 \u0254\u02d0li\u02d0|pron}} ; born 22 February 1952), more commonly known as '''KP Sharma Oli''', is a Nepalese politician and the current [[Prime Minister of Nepal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Oli appointed as 41st PM of Nepal\n|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/news/36371/|website=My Republica Online|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2018/02/kp-sharma-oli-appointed-nepal-prime-minister-180215113017547.html|title=KP Sharma Oli appointed Nepal's new prime minister|website=www.aljazeera.com|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bolchhanepal.com/oli-41st-pm-nepal/|title=Oli as 41st PM of Nepal \u2013 Bolchha Nepal|date=15 February 2018|work=Bolchha Nepal|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref> Oli previously served as prime minister from 11 October 2015 to 3 August 2016 and was the first elected prime minister under the newly adopted [[Constitution of Nepal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Oli I elected 38th Prime Minister of Nepal (Update)|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2015-10-11/oli-elected-38th-pm-of-nepal.html|website=The Kathmandu Post|accessdate=11 October 2015}}</ref>\n \n[[File:The Chairman CPN UML, Shri KP Oli meeting the Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi, in Kathmandu, Nepal on August 04, 2014.jpg|250px|thumb|right|KP Oli meeting with Narendra Modi]]\n\n[[File:The Prime Minister of Nepal, Shri K.P. Sharma Oli calling on the President, Shri Pranab Mukherjee, at Rashtrapati Bhavan, in New Delhi on February 20, 2016.jpg|250px|thumb|right|KP Oli with former president of India Pranab Mukherjee]]\n\n== Personal life ==\nKhadga Prasad Sharma Oli was born on 22 February 1952 in a [[Brahmin]] family<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nepalitimes.com/blogs/thebrief/2015/10/11/the-original-maoist/|title=The Original Maoist|publisher=Nepali Times|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.catchnews.com/international-news/kp-sharma-oli-why-nepal-s-new-pm-isn-t-the-right-man-for-the-job-1444823268.html|title=KP Sharma Oli-why Nepal's new PM isn't the right man for the job|publisher=catchnews.com|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref> at [[Terathum]]. He is the eldest child of Mohan Prasad and Madhumaya Oli.Oli was born to a humble family of farmers.<ref name=site>https://kpsharmaoli.com.np/index.php?/facetoface/detail/power-of-purpose-prime-minister-k-p-sharma-oli</ref> Oli was raised by his grandmother, Rammaya after his mother died of smallpox when Oli was four.<ref>{{cite web|title=Read a brief biography on newly elected PM KP Sharma Oli|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2015-10-11/here-is-a-biography-of-newly-elected-pm-oli.html|website=The Kathmandu Post|publisher=Kantipur Publications|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref> He did his primary school education in Tehrathum and later his family migrated to the southeastern district of [[Jhapa]]. He resided mostly in Jhapa during his early political life. Oli started his studies at [[Himalaya Higher Secondary School, Damak, Jhapa|Himalaya Higher Secondary School]] in [[Damak]] municipality of Jhapa district at the age of 12 after he migrated to [[Jhapa District]] in  1963 AD.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bharadwaj |first1=Dr. Narad |title=A Leader Who Stands Out From The Crowd |url=http://therisingnepal.org.np/news/7240 |accessdate=6 March 2020 |agency=Gorakhapatra |publisher=The Rising Nepal}}</ref> He completed his studies till ISc. In fact, he had also appeared the exam of BA first year but didn't proceed with his education further. He also served as a School teacher for Science, Maths in a local school of [[Jhapa District]]. Oli met his wife, Radhika Shakya, a fellow communist, after coming out of prison. They first met in the course of party activities and married later.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeevan saathi with Mr & Mrs. K.P. Oli|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E3a0ZUquya4|website=YouTube|publisher=Himalaya TV|accessdate=8 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Political life ==\n=== Marxist insurgency years 1966\u20131991 ===\nOli began his political career in 1966 in opposition to the partyless [[Panchayat System]] in place at the time. He joined the Communist Party of Nepal in February 1970.  He became involved in subversive politics and was arrested for the first time in 1970. A year later he became a district committee member of the party and soon the chief of the Jhapa Movement Organizing Committee in 1972. Oli was imprisoned for 14 consecutive years from 1973 to 1987. After his release from prison in 1987, he became a central committee member of UML  in-charge of the  [[Lumbini Zone]] until 1990.\n\n=== Multi-party democracy 1991\u20132006 ===\nAfter the [[1990 People's Movement]], he was elected as a member of parliament from [[Jhapa]] constituency no. 6 in 1991. He held the post of chief of the foreign department of the CPN (UML) in 1992.\n\nHe was re-elected to parliament in 1994 and served as [[Ministry of Home Affairs (Nepal)|Minister of Home Affairs]] in [[Manmohan Adhikari]]'s minority government. He was re-elected to the House of Representatives from [[Jhapa]] constituencies 2 and 6 in 1999 and gave up his Jhapa-6 seat.\n\n===Involvement in Mahakali Treaty===\nK.P. Oli has been accused of playing a significant role in the Mahakali Treaty signed in 1998 which has allowed Indian SSB forces to encroach Nepalese lands. For his involvement in this treaty, Oli has been named as ''the traitor'' by segments of Nepal.<ref name=\"Mahakali\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.groundreport.com/uml-leader-accuses-maoists-of-having-assassinated-madan-bhandari/ |title = UML leader accuses Maoists of having assassinated Madan Bhandari|date = 24 May 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Transition period ===\nOli was appointed as [[Deputy Prime Minister]] and [[Minister of Foreign Affairs]] as part of the interim government of [[Girija Prasad Koirala]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/4969422.stm | title=Nepal calls ceasefire with rebels | publisher=[[BBC]] | date=3 May 2006 | accessdate=15 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Moriarty|first1=James|title=Seven Cabinet Members Formed|url=https://www.wikileaks.org/plusd/cables/06KATHMANDU1090_a.html|website=Wikileaks|publisher=US Embassy, Kathmandu|accessdate=21 September 2015|date= 2 May 2006}}</ref> He was also assigned to look into the death of fellow politician [[Madan Bhandari]].\n\nOli was defeated in the [[2008 Nepalese Constituent Assembly election|2008 Constituent Assembly election]] from Jhapa-7. He also lost the election for the position of Chairman to [[Jhala Nath Khanal]] during the eight general congress of CPN-UML in 2009.\n\nHe was elected from Jhapa-7 in the [[2013 Nepalese Constituent Assembly election|2013 Constituent Assembly election]] and became leader of the CPN-UML Parliamentary Party on 4 February 2014, defeating party Chairman Jhala Nath Khanal by a vote of 98 to 75.<ref>{{cite news|title=Oli elected as UML PP leader|url=http://www.ekantipur.com/2014/02/04/top-story/oli-elected-as-uml-pp-leader/384914.html|accessdate=4 February 2014|newspaper=eKantipur|date=4 February 2014|archive-url=https://archive.is/20140204150108/http://www.ekantipur.com/2014/02/04/top-story/oli-elected-as-uml-pp-leader/384914.html|archive-date=4 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Oli was subsequently elected as the Chairman of CPN-UML in July 2014 during the ninth general congress.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehimalayantimes.com/fullNews.php?headline=KP+Oli+elected+as+CPN-UML+chairman&NewsID=421225|title=The Himalayan Times: Oli elected UML chairman mixed results in other posts \u2013 Detail News: Nepal News Portal|date=15 July 2014|work= The Himalayan Times|accessdate=15 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.myrepublica.com/portal/index.php?action=news_details&news_id=79047|title=Nepal congratulates Oli for election victory|publisher=Myrepublica.com|date=15 July 2014|accessdate=15 July 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718231441/http://www.myrepublica.com/portal/index.php?action=news_details&news_id=79047|archive-date=18 July 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== First prime ministership ===\nHe was elected as Prime Minister in a parliamentary vote on 11 October 2015, receiving 338 votes out of 597. Oli's PM candidacy is supported by the [[Unified Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]], [[Rastriya Prajatantra Party Nepal]], and Madhesi Rights Forum-Democratic along with 13 other small parties. He was sworn in on 12 October.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/nepals-premier-names-protest-group-leaders-deputies-095943171.html \"Nepal's new premier names protest group leaders as deputies\"], Associated Press, 12 October 2015.</ref>\n\nHis first stint was dominated by the economic [[2015 Nepal blockade|blockade]] imposed by [[India]] upon the promulgation of the [[Constitution of Nepal]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sharma|first1=Bhadra|title=Nepal's Prime Minister, K. P. Sharma Oli, Resigns Ahead of a No-Confidence Vote|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/25/world/asia/nepal-prime-minister-resigns.html|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=16 February 2018|date=24 July 2016}}</ref> He took a defiant stance against India's position to amend the constitution and signed trade and transit treaties with [[China]] to counter Indian dependence.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oli once more|url=http://www.nepalitimes.com/blogs/thebrief/2018/02/15/oli-once-more/|website=Nepali Times|publisher=Himal Media Pvt Ltd|accessdate=17 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the withdrawal of support from the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist-Centre)]] on 13 July 2016 from the existing coalition government and subsequent registration of a no-confidence motion by the party on 14 July 2016, CPN-UML and acting Prime Minister KP Oli seemingly shrank to a minority which pressured him to resign. But CPN-UML's decision to discuss filed no-confidence motion led to a three-day parliament meeting of the concerned parties. During the process, two other major parties, [[Rastriya Prajatantra Party]] and Madhesi Rights Forum-Democratic, also removed their support from the coalition. On the third day, 24 July 2016, after addressing the opposition parties in parliament, Oli announced his resignation.\n\n=== Second prime ministership ===\nOli was appointed as [[Prime Minister of Nepal]] for second time<ref>{{cite web|title=KP Oli becomes Prime Minister of Nepal for the second time|url=https://kathmandutribune.com/kp-oli-becomes-prime-minister-nepal-second-time/|website=Kathmandu Tribune|publisher=Nepal Tribune Media|accessdate=6 March 2018|date=15 February 2018}}</ref> on 15 February 2018 after CPN-UML became the largest party in the [[House of Representatives (Nepal)|House of Representatives]] following the [[2017 Nepalese legislative election|2017 legislative elections]] with support from [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist Centre)]], the same party whose withdrawal of support had led to resignation in his first term.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sharma|first1=Gopal|title=Moderate Nepali communist Oli to 'balance China, India' as new PM|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nepal-politics/moderate-nepali-communist-oli-to-balance-china-india-as-new-pm-idUSKCN1FZ0NS?il=0|newspaper=Reuters|agency=Thomson Reuters|accessdate=16 February 2018|date=15 February 2018}}</ref> He passed a [[motion of confidence]] with on 11 March 2018 with 208 out of 268 votes in the 275-member House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0927\u093e\u0928\u092e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940 \u0913\u0932\u0940\u0915\u093e \u092a\u0915\u094d\u0937\u092e\u093e \u096d\u096b \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0924\u093f\u0936\u0924 \u0938\u093e\u0902\u0938\u0926 |url=https://setopati.com/politics/140412 |website=Setopati.com |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref> He has faced criticism for inaction even with a two thirds majority in both houses of Parliament.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kainee|first1=David|title=Five months of inaction |url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/five-months-of-inaction/ |website=myrepublica |publisher=Nepal Republic Media |accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Nepal: Five Months of Oli's Rule: A Disappointment? |url=http://www.indiandefencereview.com/nepal-five-months-of-olis-rule-a-disappointment/ |website=Indian Defense Review |accessdate=9 December 2018|date=9 August 2018 }}</ref> He has also been criticized for the early release of convicted murderer Balkrishna Dhungel and protection of the murderers of [[Nirmala Panta rape case|Nirmala Panta]] leading to nationwide protests.<ref>{{cite web |title=Don't do it |url=https://myrepublica.nagariknetwork.com/news/dhungel-case/ |website=myrepublica |accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Nirmala rape, murder: Protests continue in several places|url=http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2018-12-03/nirmala-rape-murder-protests-continue-in-several-places.html |website=Kathmandu Post |publisher=Kantipur Publications |accessdate=9 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nHis government was forced to backtrack on several initiatives in quick succession in 2019. It started with the withdrawing of the Guthi Bill from the upper house.<ref>{{cite web |title=Government withdraws controversial Guthi Bill |url=https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/government-withdraws-controversial-guthi-bill/ |website=Himalayan Times |accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref> This was followed by the reversal on the cabinet decision to host [[International Indian Film Academy Awards|IIFA awards]] after a parliamentary committee instructed the government to cancel its support to the event.<ref>{{cite web |title=House panel instructs government not to host IIFA awards in Kathmandu |url=https://kathmandupost.com/politics/2019/07/02/house-panel-instructs-government-not-to-host-iifa-awards-in-kathmandu |website=kathmandupost.com |accessdate=24 August 2019 |language=English}}</ref> Oli faced criticism from lawmakers of his own party over the decision to cancel checking on agricultural goods imported from India for pesticides.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pradhan |first1=Tika R |title=As party lawmakers criticize government, Oli instructs them to speak in defense |url=https://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2019-07-07/as-party-lawmakers-criticise-government-oli-instructs-them-to-speak-in-defence.html |website=The Kathmandu Post |accessdate=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nOne of his closest ally and government spokesperson [[Gokul Prasad Baskota]] resigned on February 20, 2020, after an audio clip surfaced of him discussing [[kickbacks]] with an agent for the procurement of secure printing press.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0939\u093e\u092e\u094d\u0930\u093e\u0915\u0941\u0930\u093e \u0938\u092e\u093e\u091a\u093e\u0930 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u092d\u093e\u0935 : \u0938\u091e\u094d\u091a\u093e\u0930\u092e\u0928\u094d\u0924\u094d\u0930\u0940\u0915\u094b \u0906\u092f\u094b \u0930\u093e\u091c\u0940\u0928\u093e\u092e\u093e |url=https://hamrakura.com/news-details/73995/2020-02-20 |website=Hamrakura |accessdate=20 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Electoral history ==\nHe was elected to the [[Pratinidhi Sabha]] from [[Jhapa]] in [[1991 Nepalese legislative election|1991]], [[1994 Nepalese legislative election|1994]] and [[1999 Nepalese legislative election|1999]] on a [[CPN-UML]] ticket.<ref>[http://www.election-commission.org.np/toptwo.php Election Commission of Nepal] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061012034141/http://www.election-commission.org.np/toptwo.php |date=12 October 2006 }}</ref> He contested and won from two constituencies in the 1999 election and gave up his Jhapa-6 seat. He lost the 2008 Constituent assembly election. Only the top two candidates are shown below.\n\n'''1991 Pratinidhi Sabha Election Jhapa-6'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Party !! Candidate !! Votes !! Status\n|-\n| [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist)|CPN-UML]] || K.P. Oli || \u2013 || Elected\n|}\n\n'''1994 Pratinidhi Sabha Election Jhapa-6'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Party !! Candidate !! Votes !! Status\n|-\n| [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist)|CPN-UML]] || K.P. Oli || 18,861 || Elected\n|-\n| [[Nepali Congress]] || [[Keshav Kumar Budhathoki]] || 14,202 || Lost\n|}\n\n'''1999 Pratinidhi Sabha Election Jhapa-2'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Party !! Candidate !! Votes !! Status\n|-\n| [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist)|CPN-UML]] || K.P. Oli || 18,909 || Elected\n|-\n| [[Nepali Congress]] || Giriraj Kumari Prasai|| 18,892 || Lost\n|}\n'''1999 Pratinidhi Sabha Election Jhapa-6'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Party !! Candidate !! Votes !! Status\n|-\n| [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist)|CPN-UML]] || K.P. Oli || 23,749 || Elected\n|-\n| [[Nepali Congress]] || Kasi Lal Tajpuriya || 19,713 || Lost\n|}\n\n'''2008 Constituent Assembly Election Jhapa-7'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Party !! Candidate !! Votes !! Status\n|-\n| [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist)|CPN-UML]] || K.P. Oli || 14,959 || Lost\n|-\n| [[Unified Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]] || [[Bishwodip Lingden Limbu]] || 16,099 || Elected\n|}\n\n'''2013 Constituent Assembly Election Jhapa-7'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Party !! Candidate !! Votes !! Status\n|-\n| [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist)|CPN-UML]] || K.P. Oli || 19,287 || Elected\n|-\n| [[Nepali Congress]] || Suresh Kumar Youngaya|| 11,041 || Lost\n|}\n\n'''2015 Parliamentary Prime Minister Election'''\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Party !! Ca