mmunist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist\u2013Leninist) politicians]]\n[[Category:Nepal Communist Party (NCP) politicians]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Nepalese Constituent Assembly]]\n[[Category:Nepalese Hindus]]\n[[Category:Nepalese prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:People from Terhathum District]]\n[[Category:Prime ministers of Nepal]]\n[[Category:People from Province No. 1]]\n", "name_user": "103.1.93.53", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KP_Sharma_Oli"}
{"title_page": "Black woodpecker", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22681382/0 |title=''Dryocopus martius'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image = BlackWoods.jpg\n| image_caption = Adult male with young\n| genus = Dryocopus\n| species = martius\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| range_map= Dryocopus martius distr.PNG\n| range_map_caption=Black woodpecker range\n| synonyms = ''Picus martius'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n[[File:Spillkr\u00e5ka trummar - Dendrocopos martius..ogg|thumb|Black woodpecker drumming]]\nThe '''black woodpecker''' (''Dryocopus martius'') is a large [[woodpecker]] that lives in mature forests across the northern [[Palearctic realm|Palearctic]]. It is the sole representative of its [[genus]] in that region. Its range is expanding. It does not [[Bird migration|migrate]]. This species is closely related to, and fills the same [[ecological niche]] in Europe as, the [[pileated woodpecker]] of [[North America]].\n\n==Range==\nThe range of the black woodpecker spreads east from [[Spain]] across the whole of [[Europe]], excluding [[Great Britain]], [[Ireland]], and northern [[Scandinavia]]. It is also native to parts of [[Asia]], including [[Korea]], [[Japan]] and [[China]], and to the [[Middle East]], including [[Iran]] and [[Kazakhstan]]. The southern limits of this woodpecker's range are in [[Spain]] and [[Italy]], and it has also been recorded as a vagrant in [[Portugal]]. The species is generally more uncommon and more discontinuous in distribution in the Asian part of its range.<ref name=\"Peterson\">Peterson, R.T., Mountfort, G. and Hollom, P.A.D. (1993) ''Collins Field Guide: Birds of Britain and Europe''. HarperCollins Publishers, London.</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Dryocopus pileatus 4zz.jpg|thumb|Skull of a black woodpecker]]\nThe black woodpecker measures {{convert|45|to|55|cm|in|abbr=on}} long with a {{convert|64|to|84|cm|in|abbr=on}} wingspan.<ref name=BWP>{{cite book |title=The Birds of the Western Palearctic [Abridged] |year=1997 |publisher=[[OUP]] |isbn=0-19-854099-X}}</ref><ref>http://www.avibirds.com/euhtml/Black_Woodpecker.html</ref><ref name=\"Winkler\">''Woodpeckers: An Identification Guide to the Woodpeckers of the World'' by Hans Winkler, David A. Christie & David Nurney. Houghton Mifflin (1995), {{ISBN|978-0395720431}}</ref> Body weight is approximately {{convert|250|to|400|g|oz|abbr=on}} on average.<ref name=\"Winkler\"/><ref>http://www.world-of-animals.de/animal-lexicon/tierart_black-woodpecker.html</ref><ref>{{cite journal|jstor=3803216|pages=1053\u20131066|last1=Rolstad|first1=J. r.|last2=Rolstad|first2=E.|last3=S\u00e6teren|first3=\u00d8y.|title=Black Woodpecker Nest Sites: Characteristics, Selection, and Reproductive Success|volume=64|issue=4|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|year=2000|doi=10.2307/3803216}}</ref><ref>Brazil, M. (2009) ''Field Guide to the Birds of East Asia: Eastern China, Taiwan, Korea, Japan and Eastern Russia''. A&C Black, London.</ref> Among standard measurements, the [[Wing chord (biology)|wing chord]] is {{convert|22.7|to|26|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the [[tail]] is {{convert|15.9|to|17.3|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the very long [[Beak|bill]] is {{convert|5|to|6.7|cm|in|abbr=on}} and the [[Tarsus (skeleton)|tarsus]] is {{convert|3.6|to|4|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Winkler\"/> It is easily the largest woodpecker in its range and is second in size only to the [[great slaty woodpecker]] amongst the woodpecker species certain to exist (with the likely [[extinction]] of the [[Imperial woodpecker|largest]] and [[ivory-billed woodpecker|second largest]] woodpeckers), although its average mass is similar to that of the [[Magellanic woodpecker]] of [[South America]]. The closely related [[Pileated woodpecker|pileated]] and [[white-bellied woodpecker]]s also broadly overlap in size with the black woodpecker, but both are somewhat smaller in average and maximal size and mass.<ref name=\"Winkler\"/><ref>http://woodpeckersofeurope.blogspot.com/search?q=black+woodpecker</ref> The [[plumage]] of this [[Carrion crow|crow-sized]] woodpecker is entirely black apart from a red crown. In males, the entire crown is red, but in females only the top hindcrown is red, with the rest of the body all black.<ref name='BWP'/> The juvenile black woodpecker is similar but is less glossy, with a duller red crown and a paler grey throat and bill .<ref name=\"Perrins\">Perrins, C.M., Attenborough, D. and Arlott, N. (1987). ''New Generation Guide to the Birds of Britain and Europe''. University of Texas Press, Texas.</ref> The piercing yellow eyes and manic, high-pitched calls of the black woodpecker have made it the villain of fairy tales throughout its range. Their voice is remarkable in that it has two different calls. One is a short single high-pitched note, a loud, whistling ''kree-kree-kree'', done only twice in a row. The other is a screech-like shrill while in flight. Unlike other woodpecker species, the black woodpecker does not have a dipping, bounding flight, but instead flies with slow, unsteady-seeming wing beats with its head raised.<ref name=\"Winkler\"/><ref name=\"Perrins\"/>\n\n==Habitat==\nThe black woodpecker is mainly found in forested regions, with a preference for extensive, mature woodland, including [[coniferous]], [[Tropical forest|tropical]], subtropical and [[Taiga|boreal forests]]. It is very widespread throughout mountainous and lowland forests. It is more likely to occur in marginal woods near human habitations during the non-breeding season. This species has been observed at elevations between {{convert|100|and|2400|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Peterson\"/><ref name=\"Winkler\"/><ref name=\"Perrins\"/>\n\n==Behaviour==\n[[File:Dryocopus martius 02.jpg|thumb|left|Tree work by black woodpecker]]\n[[File:Dryocopus martius MWNH 2211.JPG|thumb|Egg, Collection [[Museum Wiesbaden]]]]\nThe woodpecker feeds by using its bill to hammer on dead trees to dig out [[carpenter ant]]s and wood-boring beetle grubs.<ref name=\"JWM\">{{cite journal\n | title=Black Woodpecker Nest Sites: Characteristics, Selection, and Reproductive Success\n | periodical=The Journal of Wildlife Management\n | publisher=Allen Press\n | volume=64\n | edition=4th\n | pages=1053\u20131066\n | year=2000\n | jstor=3803216\n | doi=10.2307/3803216\n | last1=Rolstad\n | first1=Jorund\n | last2=Rolstad\n | first2=E.\n | last3=S\u00e6teren\n | first3=\u00d8y.\n | issue=4\n}}</ref> The selection of foods is relatively predictable, narrow and consistent in this species.<ref name= Mikusinski>Mikusi\u0144ski, G. (1995). Population trends in black woodpecker in relation to changes and characteristics of European forests. Ecography, 18(4), 363-369.</ref> Like all woodpeckers, this species has a specially adapted neck containing very strong muscles, which allow it to endlessly hack away at tree bark. Due to the size of its bill and large size and great physical power of this bird, it can access prey fairly deep within a tree. In order to position itself correctly, it has short, stumpy legs, as well as long, sharp claws and very stiff tail feathers. The woodpecker will more than likely choose a tree with a fungal disease, such as heart rot, although some will utilise a living, healthy tree. Once a hole has been made, the black woodpecker chips downwards through the trunk of the tree, creating a nesting chamber, the only lining being the woodchips created throughout the process. The black woodpecker's excavations provide homes for many other species of bird and mammal, and is therefore considered to be a \"keystone\" species in many of its habitats throughout its range. It not only provides habitats for other species, but also controls populations of wood-boring insects, helping to protect the trees.<ref name=\"Perrins\"/><ref>Gorman, G. (2008) ''Central and Eastern European Wildlife''. Bradt Travel Guides, Buckshire.</ref>\n\nWhen the nest is ready, the female lays a single clutch of two to eight eggs, the average being four to six. The nest hole is usually dug in a live poplar or pine tree.<ref name=\"JWM\"/> The breeding pair take it in turns to incubate the eggs, also sharing duties of feeding and brooding the chicks once they have hatched. The nestlings may fight their way to the entrance of the nest in order to be fed first. After 18 to 35 days, the young black woodpeckers will leave the nest, staying with the adults for another week.<ref name=\"Winkler\"/><ref name=\"Perrins\"/>\n\n==Mortality and status==\nThe black woodpecker is a fairly widely distributed woodland species and can successfully breed in most areas where extensive woodland is left. At one point, when much of Europe and Asia was deforested, this species declined and in some areas is still struggling today, including in the [[Pyrenees]]. They normally require mature trees and ample stands of dead trees to sustain a viable breeding population.<ref>Garmendia, A., C\u00e1rcamo, S., & Schwendtner, O. (2006). ''Forest management considerations for conservation of black woodpecker ''Dryocopus martius'' and white-backed woodpecker ''Dendrocopos leucotos'' populations in Quinto Real (Spanish Western Pyrenees)''. In Forest Diversity and Management (pp. 339-355). Springer Netherlands.</ref> However, with the restoration of some forested areas, black woodpeckers have increased in some parts of Europe.<ref name= Mikusinski/> They are occasionally considered a nuisance species due to their damage to power lines, communication poles and houses, occasionally resulting in woodpecker mortality due to electrocution or being culled by humans.<ref>Turcek, F. J. (1960). ''On the damage by birds to power and communication lines''. Bird Study, 7(4), 231-236.</ref> The main cause of nesting failures appears to be predation.<ref>Martin, T. E. (1993). ''Evolutionary determinants of clutch size in cavity-nesting birds: nest predation or limited breeding opportunities?'' American Naturalist, 937-946.</ref> Their main natural predator is the [[pine marten]] (''Martes martes''), which feeds on eggs, nestlings and brooding females and then often takes over the nest hole of the woodpeckers for its own.<ref>Nilsson, S. G., Johnsson, K., & Tjernberg, M. (1991). ''Is avoidance by black woodpeckers of old nest holes due to predators?'' Animal Behaviour, 41(3), 439-441.</ref> Other than the marten, there are notably few known natural predators of black woodpeckers.<ref>Pacl\u00edk, M., Mis\u00edk, J., & Weidinger, K. (2009, January). ''Nest predation and nest defence in European and North American woodpeckers: a review''. In Annales Zoologici Fennici (pp. 361-379). Finnish Zoological and Botanical Publishing Board.</ref> [[Western jackdaw]]s (''Corvus monedula'') are notably regular usurpers of this species' nest holes and a potential predator of eggs and small nestlings.<ref>Johnsson, K. (1994). ''Colonial breeding and nest predation in the jackdaw ''Corvus monedula'' using old black woodpecker ''Dryocopus martius'' holes''. Ibis, 136(3), 313-317.</ref> A few of the larger birds of prey that can hunt in woodlands may prey on black woodpeckers. Among those recorded are [[Ural owl]]s (''Strix uralensis''),<ref>Lundberg, A. (1981). ''Population ecology of the Ural owl ''Strix uralensis'' in central Sweden''. Ornis Scandinavica, 111-119.</ref> [[Eurasian eagle-owl]]s (''Bubo bubo''),<ref name= Wassink>Wassink, G. (2010). ''Het dieet van de Oehoe in Nederland en enkele aangrenzende gebieden in Duitsland''. Limosa. 83: 97-108.</ref> [[northern goshawk]]s (''Accipiter gentilis''),<ref>Opdam, P., Thissen, J., Verschuren, P., & M\u00fcskens, G. (1977). ''Feeding ecology of a population of Goshawk ''Accipiter gentilis''''. Journal of Ornithology, 118(1), 35-51.</ref> [[common buzzard]]s (''Buteo buteo'')<ref>\u0160otn\u00e1r, K., & Obuch, J. (2009). ''Feeding ecology of a nesting population of the Common Buzzard (''Buteo buteo'') in the Upper Nitra Region, Central Slovakia''. Slovak Raptor Journal, 3, 13-20.</ref> and [[golden eagle]]s (''Aquila chrysaetos'').\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Commons|Dryocopus martius}}\n* Gorman, Gerard (2004): ''Woodpeckers of Europe: A Study of the European Picidae''. Bruce Coleman, UK. {{ISBN|1-872842-05-4}}.\n* Gorman, Gerard (2011): ''The Black Woodpecker: A monograph on ''Dryocopus martius'' ''. Lynx Edicions, Barcelona. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-79-8}}.\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q143284}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:woodpecker, black}}\n[[Category:Dryocopus|black woodpecker]]\n[[Category:Birds of Eurasia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Russia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|black woodpecker]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22681382/0 |title=''Dryocopus martius'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| image = BlackWoods.jpg\n| image_caption = Adult male with young\n| genus = Dryocopus\n| species = martius\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]], [[10th edition of Systema Naturae|1758]])\n| range_map= Dryocopus martius distr.PNG\n| range_map_caption=Black woodpecker range\n| synonyms = ''Picus martius'' {{small|Linnaeus,&nbsp;1758}}\n}}\n[[File:Spillkr\u00e5ka trummar - Dendrocopos martius..ogg|thumb|Black woodpecker drumming]]\nThe '''black woodpecker''' (''Dryocopus martius'') is a large [[woodpecker]] that lives in mature forests across the northern [[Palearctic realm|Palearctic]]. It is the sole representative of its [[genus]] in that region. Its range is expanding. It does not [[Bird migration|migrate]]. This species is closely related to, and fills the same [[ecological niche]] in Europe as, the [[pileated woodpecker]] of [[North America]].\n\n==Range==\nThe range of the black woodpecker spreads east from [[Spain]] across the whole of [[Europe]], excluding [[Great Britain]], [[Ireland]], and northern [[Scandinavia]]. It is also native to parts of [[Asia]], including [[Korea]], [[Japan]] and [[China]], and to the [[Middle East]], including [[Iran]] and [[Kazakhstan]]. The southern limits of this woodpecker's range are in [[Spain]] and [[Italy]], and it has also been recorded as a vagrant in [[Portugal]]. The species is generally more uncommon and more discontinuous in distribution in the Asian part of its range.<ref name=\"Peterson\">Peterson, R.T., Mountfort, G. and Hollom, P.A.D. (1993) ''Collins Field Guide: Birds of Britain and Europe''. HarperCollins Publishers, London.</ref>\n\n==Description==\n[[File:Dryocopus pileatus 4zz.jpg|thumb|Skull of a black woodpecker]]\nThe black woodpecker measures {{convert|45|to|55|cm|in|abbr=on}} long with a {{convert|64|to|84|cm|in|abbr=on}} wingspan.<ref name=BWP>{{cite book |title=The Birds of the Western Palearctic [Abridged] |year=1997 |publisher=[[OUP]] |isbn=0-19-854099-X}}</ref><ref>http://www.avibirds.com/euhtml/Black_Woodpecker.html</ref><ref name=\"Winkler\">''Woodpeckers: An Identification Guide to the Woodpeckers of the World'' by Hans Winkler, David A. Christie & David Nurney. Houghton Mifflin (1995), {{ISBN|978-0395720431}}</ref> Body weight is approximately {{convert|250|to|400|g|oz|abbr=on}} on average.<ref name=\"Winkler\"/><ref>http://www.world-of-animals.de/animal-lexicon/tierart_black-woodpecker.html</ref><ref>{{cite journal|jstor=3803216|pages=1053\u20131066|last1=Rolstad|first1=J. r.|last2=Rolstad|first2=E.|last3=S\u00e6teren|first3=\u00d8y.|title=Black Woodpecker Nest Sites: Characteristics, Selection, and Reproductive Success|volume=64|issue=4|journal=The Journal of Wildlife Management|year=2000|doi=10.2307/3803216}}</ref><ref>Brazil, M. (2009) ''Field Guide to the Birds of East Asia: Eastern China, Taiwan, Korea, Japan and Eastern Russia''. A&C Black, London.</ref> Among standard measurements, the [[Wing chord (biology)|wing chord]] is {{convert|22.7|to|26|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the [[tail]] is {{convert|15.9|to|17.3|cm|in|abbr=on}}, the very long [[Beak|bill]] is {{convert|5|to|6.7|cm|in|abbr=on}} and the [[Tarsus (skeleton)|tarsus]] is {{convert|3.6|to|4|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Winkler\"/> It is easily the largest woodpecker in its range and is second in size only to the [[great slaty woodpecker]] amongst the woodpecker species certain to exist (with the likely [[extinction]] of the [[Imperial woodpecker|largest]] and [[ivory-billed woodpecker|second largest]] woodpeckers), although its average mass is similar to that of the [[Magellanic woodpecker]] of [[South America]]. The closely related [[Pileated woodpecker|pileated]] and [[white-bellied woodpecker]]s also broadly overlap in size with the black woodpecker, but both are somewhat smaller in average and maximal size and mass.<ref name=\"Winkler\"/><ref>http://woodpeckersofeurope.blogspot.com/search?q=black+woodpecker</ref> The [[plumage]] of this [[Carrion crow|crow-sized]] woodpecker is entirely black apart from a red crown. In males, the entire crown is red, but in females only the top hindcrown is red, with the rest of the body all black.<ref name='BWP'/> The juvenile black woodpecker is similar but is less glossy, with a duller red crown and a paler grey throat and bill .<ref name=\"Perrins\">Perrins, C.M., Attenborough, D. and Arlott, N. (1987). ''New Generation Guide to the Birds of Britain and Europe''. University of Texas Press, Texas.</ref> The piercing yellow eyes and manic, high-pitched calls of the black woodpecker have made it the villain of fairy tales throughout its range. Their voice is remarkable in that it has two different calls. One is a short single high-pitched note, a loud, whistling ''kree-kree-kree'', done only twice in a row. The other is a screech-like shrill while in flight. Unlike other woodpecker species, the black woodpecker does not have a dipping, bounding flight, but instead flies with slow, unsteady-seeming wing beats with its head raised.<ref name=\"Winkler\"/><ref name=\"Perrins\"/>\n\n==Habitat==\nThe black woodpecker is mainly found in forested regions, with a preference for extensive, mature woodland, including [[coniferous]], [[Tropical forest|tropical]], subtropical and [[Taiga|boreal forests]]. It is very widespread throughout mountainous and lowland forests. It is more likely to occur in marginal woods near human habitations during the non-breeding season. This species has been observed at elevations between {{convert|100|and|2400|m|ft|abbr=on}}.<ref name=\"Peterson\"/><ref name=\"Winkler\"/><ref name=\"Perrins\"/>\n\n==Behaviour==\n[[File:Dryocopus martius 02.jpg|thumb|left|Tree work by black woodpecker]]\n[[File:Dryocopus martius MWNH 2211.JPG|thumb|Egg, Collection [[Museum Wiesbaden]]]]\nThe woodpecker feeds by using its bill to hammer on dead trees to dig out [[carpenter ant]]s and wood-boring beetle grubs.<ref name=\"JWM\">{{cite journal\n | title=Black Woodpecker Nest Sites: Characteristics, Selection, and Reproductive Success\n | periodical=The Journal of Wildlife Management\n | publisher=Allen Press\n | volume=64\n | edition=4th\n | pages=1053\u20131066\n | year=2000\n | jstor=3803216\n | doi=10.2307/3803216\n | last1=Rolstad\n | first1=Jorund\n | last2=Rolstad\n | first2=E.\n | last3=S\u00e6teren\n | first3=\u00d8y.\n | issue=4\n}}</ref> The selection of foods is relatively predictible, narrow and consistent in this species.<ref name= Mikusinski>Mikusi\u0144ski, G. (1995). Population trends in black woodpecker in relation to changes and characteristics of European forests. Ecography, 18(4), 363-369.</ref> Like all woodpeckers, this species has a specially adapted neck containing very strong muscles, which allow it to endlessly hack away at tree bark. Due to the size of its bill and large size and great physical power of this bird, it can access prey fairly deep within a tree. In order to position itself correctly, it has short, stumpy legs, as well as long, sharp claws and very stiff tail feathers. The woodpecker will more than likely choose a tree with a fungal disease, such as heart rot, although some will utilise a living, healthy tree. Once a hole has been made, the black woodpecker chips downwards through the trunk of the tree, creating a nesting chamber, the only lining being the woodchips created throughout the process. The black woodpecker's excavations provide homes for many other species of bird and mammal, and is therefore considered to be a \"keystone\" species in many of its habitats throughout its range. It not only provides habitats for other species, but also controls populations of wood-boring insects, helping to protect the trees.<ref name=\"Perrins\"/><ref>Gorman, G. (2008) ''Central and Eastern European Wildlife''. Bradt Travel Guides, Buckshire.</ref>\n\nWhen the nest is ready, the female lays a single clutch of two to eight eggs, the average being four to six. The nest hole is usually dug in a live poplar or pine tree.<ref name=\"JWM\"/> The breeding pair take it in turns to incubate the eggs, also sharing duties of feeding and brooding the chicks once they have hatched. The nestlings may fight their way to the entrance of the nest in order to be fed first. After 18 to 35 days, the young black woodpeckers will leave the nest, staying with the adults for another week.<ref name=\"Winkler\"/><ref name=\"Perrins\"/>\n\n==Mortality and status==\nThe black woodpecker is a fairly widely distributed woodland species and can successfully breed in most areas where extensive woodland is left. At one point, when much of Europe and Asia was deforested, this species declined and in some areas is still struggling today, including in the [[Pyrenees]]. They normally require mature trees and ample stands of dead trees to sustain a viable breeding population.<ref>Garmendia, A., C\u00e1rcamo, S., & Schwendtner, O. (2006). ''Forest management considerations for conservation of black woodpecker ''Dryocopus martius'' and white-backed woodpecker ''Dendrocopos leucotos'' populations in Quinto Real (Spanish Western Pyrenees)''. In Forest Diversity and Management (pp. 339-355). Springer Netherlands.</ref> However, with the restoration of some forested areas, black woodpeckers have increased in some parts of Europe.<ref name= Mikusinski/> They are occasionally considered a nuisance species due to their damage to power lines, communication poles and houses, occasionally resulting in woodpecker mortality due to electrocution or being culled by humans.<ref>Turcek, F. J. (1960). ''On the damage by birds to power and communication lines''. Bird Study, 7(4), 231-236.</ref> The main cause of nesting failures appears to be predation.<ref>Martin, T. E. (1993). ''Evolutionary determinants of clutch size in cavity-nesting birds: nest predation or limited breeding opportunities?'' American Naturalist, 937-946.</ref> Their main natural predator is the [[pine marten]] (''Martes martes''), which feeds on eggs, nestlings and brooding females and then often takes over the nest hole of the woodpeckers for its own.<ref>Nilsson, S. G., Johnsson, K., & Tjernberg, M. (1991). ''Is avoidance by black woodpeckers of old nest holes due to predators?'' Animal Behaviour, 41(3), 439-441.</ref> Other than the marten, there are notably few known natural predators of black woodpeckers.<ref>Pacl\u00edk, M., Mis\u00edk, J., & Weidinger, K. (2009, January). ''Nest predation and nest defence in European and North American woodpeckers: a review''. In Annales Zoologici Fennici (pp. 361-379). Finnish Zoological and Botanical Publishing Board.</ref> [[Western jackdaw]]s (''Corvus monedula'') are notably regular usurpers of this species' nest holes and a potential predator of eggs and small nestlings.<ref>Johnsson, K. (1994). ''Colonial breeding and nest predation in the jackdaw ''Corvus monedula'' using old black woodpecker ''Dryocopus martius'' holes''. Ibis, 136(3), 313-317.</ref> A few of the larger birds of prey that can hunt in woodlands may prey on black woodpeckers. Among those recorded are [[Ural owl]]s (''Strix uralensis''),<ref>Lundberg, A. (1981). ''Population ecology of the Ural owl ''Strix uralensis'' in central Sweden''. Ornis Scandinavica, 111-119.</ref> [[Eurasian eagle-owl]]s (''Bubo bubo''),<ref name= Wassink>Wassink, G. (2010). ''Het dieet van de Oehoe in Nederland en enkele aangrenzende gebieden in Duitsland''. Limosa. 83: 97-108.</ref> [[northern goshawk]]s (''Accipiter gentilis''),<ref>Opdam, P., Thissen, J., Verschuren, P., & M\u00fcskens, G. (1977). ''Feeding ecology of a population of Goshawk ''Accipiter gentilis''''. Journal of Ornithology, 118(1), 35-51.</ref> [[common buzzard]]s (''Buteo buteo'')<ref>\u0160otn\u00e1r, K., & Obuch, J. (2009). ''Feeding ecology of a nesting population of the Common Buzzard (''Buteo buteo'') in the Upper Nitra Region, Central Slovakia''. Slovak Raptor Journal, 3, 13-20.</ref> and [[golden eagle]]s (''Aquila chrysaetos'').\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{Commons|Dryocopus martius}}\n* Gorman, Gerard (2004): ''Woodpeckers of Europe: A Study of the European Picidae''. Bruce Coleman, UK. {{ISBN|1-872842-05-4}}.\n* Gorman, Gerard (2011): ''The Black Woodpecker: A monograph on ''Dryocopus martius'' ''. Lynx Edicions, Barcelona. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-79-8}}.\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q143284}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:woodpecker, black}}\n[[Category:Dryocopus|black woodpecker]]\n[[Category:Birds of Eurasia]]\n[[Category:Birds of Russia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1758|black woodpecker]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Black_woodpecker"}
{"title_page": "Caroline Palavicino-Maggio", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Caroline Palavicino-Maggio\n| image             = File:Caroline Palavicino-Maggio.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = Harlem, New York City\n| nationality       = Latin American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Harvard Medical School\n| alma_mater        = B.S. Rider College, PhD New Jersey Medical School at Rutgers University, postdoctoral work Harvard Medical School\n| known_for         = Neural circuits underlying aggression in female Drosophila\n| awards            = 2016 Society for Translational and Academic Researcher Fellow, 2012 New York Academy of Sciences with PepsiCo. R&D Young Scientist Award, 2008 Alfred P. Sloan Foundation, Pre-doctoral Sloan Scholar, 2008 Rutgers University Honor Society for Research Scholars, 1998 Scholarship Recipient, Unilever Research, 1998   Eleanor Humanitarian Award\n| Institutions      = Harvard Medical School\n}}\n\n'''Caroline Palavicino-Maggio''' is a Latin American neuroscientist and Research Fellow in the Department of Neurobiology at [[Harvard Medical School]]. Palavicino-Maggio explores how gene expression in amine neurons and neural circuits leads to changes in social behavior, specifically aggression, in Drosophila. Palavicino-Maggio is committed to mentoring and inspiring first-generation students in STEM and serves as the Director of Outreach for the Journal of Emerging Investigators, an open-access journal  that publishes research conducted by middle and high school students as a means to expose young and underrepresented future scientists to academic research and the publishing process.\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nPalavicino-Maggio was born in [[Harlem]] and grew up in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://brain.harvard.edu/hbi_humans/caroline-palavicino-maggio/|title=Caroline Palavicino-Maggio|website=Harvard Brain Science Initiative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Her mother was an immigrant from [[Colombia]] and her father was an immigrant from [[Chile]]. Later in her childhood, Palavicino-Maggio's family moved across the river to a small factory town in New Jersey called Edgewater where her mother worked in retail and her father worked as an elevator mechanic.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nPalavicino-Maggio was 13 years old, her sister ended her own life.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://storiesinscience.org/2020/03/10/humans-of-hbi-caroline-palavicino-maggio/|title=Humans of HBI: Caroline Palavicino-Maggio|date=2020-03-11|website=Stories in Science|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> This life-altering experience motivated Palavicino-Maggio to focus her career on neuroscience, specifically neurochemistry in the context of behavior.<ref name=\":1\" /> Further, Palavicino-Maggio experienced violent crimes in the various neighbourhoods she lived as a child, and this experience further motivated her to study the neurobiology of aggression as well as focus her work towards one day contributing to criminal psychology, law to effect change at the societal level.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nWith her drive to study neuroscience, Palavicino-Maggio attended [[Rider University|Rider College]] for her undergraduate education.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.emerginginvestigators.org/staff|title=Staff {{!}} Journal of Emerging Investigators|last=JEI|website=www.emerginginvestigators.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> She majored in biopsychology and political sociology<ref name=\":2\" /> becoming the first female in her family to pursue post-secondary education.<ref name=\":0\" /> Palavicino-Maggio graduated from Rider University in 2002 with a Bachelors of Science and then pursued research experience at both Rockefeller University and Columbia University as a research assistant\u00a0from 2002 to 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://njms.rutgers.edu/departments/pharmacology/graduate_students.cfm|title=Rutgers New Jersey Medical School|website=njms.rutgers.edu|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> During this time, Palavicino-Maggio had the opportunity to present her research at the [[Society for Neuroscience]] conference, and on her way there sat next to Dr. Nick Ingolglia, the Associate Dean of [[New Jersey Medical School]] at [[Rutgers University]] and he inspired her to pursue graduate education.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2009, Palavicino-Maggio began her graduate degree at [[New Jersey Medical School|Rutgers University at New Jersey Medical School]] in the Department of Pharmacology and Physiology.<ref name=\":2\" /> Under the mentorship of Dr. Andrew Thomas and Dr. Eldo Kuzhikandathil, Palavicino-Maggio focused her graduate work in looking at the effects of neuropsychiatric drugs on weight gain.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|last2=Kuzhikandathil|first2=Eldo V.|date=09 2016|title=Dietary Fructose and GLUT5 Transporter Activity Contribute to Antipsychotic-Induced Weight Gain|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27056716|journal=Schizophrenia Bulletin|volume=42|issue=5|pages=1270\u20131279|doi=10.1093/schbul/sbw037|issn=1745-1701|pmc=4988743|pmid=27056716}}</ref> One of the many reasons that patients stop taking medication to treat mental illness is due to side effects like weight gain.<ref name=\":3\" /> Understanding how these side effects manifest as a means to find ways to alleviate them may help with patient compliance, health, and wellbeing.<ref name=\":3\" /> Palavicino-Maggio hypothesized that [[antipsychotic]]s modulate [[fructose]] absorption in the intestine by affecting GLUT5 function, a transporter for fructose, and thus contributing to weight gain.<ref name=\":3\" /> \u00a0Palavicino-Maggio found that [[clozapine]], a typical antipsychotic, induced weight gain in mice and increased fructose uptake by the intestinal GLUT5 transporter though it did not increase expression of the transporter.<ref name=\":3\" /> They further found this transporter to be essential for antipsychotic induced weight gain.<ref name=\":3\" /> Interestingly, clozapine also seemed to slow blood glucose lowering and protein lipogenesis.<ref name=\":3\" /> \u00a0Palavicino-Maggio graduated with a PhD in Neuropharmacology and Neurophysiology in 2013 and her thesis was titled \"Effect of Antipsychotics on the Enteric Nervous System: Implications for Weight Gain\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Effect_of_Antipsychotics_on_the_Enteric.html?id=tARJngEACAAJ|title=Effect of Antipsychotics on the Enteric Nervous System: Implications for Weight Gain|date=2013|publisher=Palavicino-Maggio|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Career and Research ==\nPalavicino-Maggio was eager to continue in academia and pursued her postdoctoral work at Harvard Medical School in 2016.<ref name=\":2\" /> Before starting in the lab, Palavicino-Maggio took a [[Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory]] course in [[Drosophila]] Neurobiology: Genes, Circuits and Behavior to prepare to work under the mentorship of Dr. Edward Kravitz at Harvard studying aggression in drosophila.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://meetings.cshl.edu/alumni.aspx?course=C-DROS&year=17|title=CSHL Meetings|website=meetings.cshl.edu|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nPalavicino-Maggio's work explores the function and cellular localization of proteins in ''Drosophila melanogaster'', fruit flies, that correlate to hyper-aggressive phenotypes.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hms.harvard.edu/bss/neuro/kravitz/people.html|title=People|website=www.hms.harvard.edu|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> By understanding the neural substrates for aggression in model organisms, Palavicino-Maggio's research sets the stage for a better understanding of how these genes drive aggressive behaviors and how they could be targeted therapeutically in patients with neuropsychiatric disorders.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nPalavicino-Maggio has explored patterns in aggressive behavior in two different species of Drosophila and found that Drosophila from cooler microclimates showed more aggression and more successful courtship behavior compared to the Drosophila from the warmer climate.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|last2=Trannoy|first2=S\u00e9verine|last3=Holton|first3=Kristina M.|last4=Song|first4=Xiaoying|last5=Li|first5=Kexin|last6=Nevo|first6=Eviatar|date=2019-03-11|title=Aggression and courtship differences found in Drosophila melanogaster from two different microclimates at Evolution Canyon, Israel|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-019-40701-8|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=9|issue=1|pages=1\u20139|doi=10.1038/s41598-019-40701-8|issn=2045-2322}}</ref> This research set the stage for Palavicino-Maggio to explore the biological basis of aggression, work that was published in the [[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]] in 2019.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|last2=Chan|first2=Yick-Bun|last3=McKellar|first3=Claire|last4=Kravitz|first4=Edward A.|date=08 20, 2019|title=A small number of cholinergic neurons mediate hyperaggression in female Drosophila|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31391301|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=116|issue=34|pages=17029\u201317038|doi=10.1073/pnas.1907042116|issn=1091-6490|pmc=6708353|pmid=31391301}}</ref> Palavicino-Maggio and her team narrowed in on the question of which neural circuits govern aggression in female flies and if this circuit is important in the expression of aggressive behavior in male flies.<ref name=\":5\" /> While it is often thought that males are more aggressive than females in most species, Palavicino-Maggio and her colleagues saw quite the opposite when they screened for aggressive behaviors in fly lines using Drosophila Flylight Gal4.<ref name=\":5\" /> They found that the GMR26E01-Gal4 line had extremelty aggressive females, but males with normal aggressive behavior. <nowiki>https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31391301</nowiki>\u00a0 Further, the fights that the females engaged in, ended in hierarchical social relationships among the flies.<ref name=\":5\" /> They then tried to hone in on which subpopulation of neurons were responsible for driving this behavior and they found 2-4 pairs of neurons in the female brain pC1 region that were cholinergic and weakly GABAergic that seemed to drive the aggressive behavior in females but did not exist in males.<ref name=\":5\" /> The fascinating finding that such a small populations of neurons can drive specific and intense behavioral outputs will serve as a critical tool and model to understand how exactly interactions between neurons drive complex behaviors and provide a stepping stone for translation into more complex models of social behavior.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Advocacy and Service ==\nPalavicino-Maggio is actively involved in promoting diversity, equity, and inclusion in her scientific community.<ref name=\":0\" /> Palavicino-Maggio\u00a0 is a board member of the Harvard Latino Alumni Association, the Outreach director of the Journal of Emerging Investigators, an appointed member of the multiple committees within in Harvard's Office for Diversity, Inclusion, and Community Partnership, and the Mentoring Director of the Health Professions Recruitment and Exposure Program at Harvard Medical School.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nJournal of Emerging Investigators, where Palavicino-Maggio holds the title Director of Outreach, is an open-access journal that publishes research conducted by middle and high school students as a means to expose young and underrepresented future scientists to academic research and the publishing process.<ref name=\":2\" /> As the Director of Outreach, Palavicino-Maggio helps to recruit submissions from students around the world, specifically Central America, South America, and Africa.<ref name=\":2\" /> One of the projects she has been working on with students from the Boston community focuses on exploring the prevalence of antibiotic resistant bacteria around Boston.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://emerginginvestigators.org/articles/investigation-of-everyday-locations-for-antibiotic-resistant-bacteria-in-cambridge-massachusetts|title=Investigation of Everyday Locations for Antibiotic-resistant Bacteria in Cambridge, Massachusetts {{!}} Journal of Emerging Investigators|website=emerginginvestigators.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \u00a0Palavicino-Maggio and her students found that of all of the colonies they grew from water fountains, traffic lights, phones, sneakers, and the Harvard T-station, only the Harvard T-station showed signs of resistant bacteria as bacterial cultures grew in the presence of ampicillin.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nWithin the Office of Diversity, Inclusion, and Community Partnership at Harvard, Palavicino-Maggio is involved in the Diversity Pipeline of Community Engagement Committee as well as the Equity, Inclusion, and Social Justice Committee, both led by Dean Joan Reede.<ref name=\":2\" /> As a Mentoring Director for Health Professions Recruitment and Exposure Program at Harvard Medical School, Palavicino-Maggio helps to equip underrepresented high school students with the proper skill sets and knowledge to succeed in STEM fields, especially in the biosciences.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nPalavicino-Maggio is also engaged in diplomacy work to bridge community and scientific connections between American and Cuban Scientists.<ref name=\":4\" /> As a part of these efforts, Palavicino-Maggio was able to host Enrique Beldarrain Chaple, the Chief of Research Department, the National Information Center of Medical Sciences and Professor of Public Health and History of\u00a0 Medicine at the National School of Public Health in Havana, Cuba.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dicp.hms.harvard.edu/sites/default/files/files/2016/Calendar/Beldarrain-Enrique.pdf|title=The Epidemic Diseases in Cuba|last=|first=|date=|website=Harvard Medical School Office for Diversity Inclusion and Community Participation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* 2016 Society for Translational and Academic Researcher Fellow, Harvard Medical School<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://connects.catalyst.harvard.edu/Profiles/display/Person/148931|title=Caroline Palavicino-Maggio {{!}} Harvard Catalyst Profiles {{!}} Harvard Catalyst|website=connects.catalyst.harvard.edu|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n* 2012 New York Academy of Sciences with PepsiCo. R&D Young Scientist Award<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 2011 NIMH Independent Research Grant - Effects of Atypical Antipsychotics on Fructose Metabolism and Weight Gain<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 2008 Alfred P. Sloan Foundation, Pre-doctoral Sloan Scholar<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 2008 Rutgers University Honor Society for Research Scholars<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 1998 Scholarship Recipient, Unilever Research, U.S.<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 1998 Eleanor Humanitarian Award<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* Palavicino-Maggio CB, Chan YB, McKellar C, Kravitz EA. A small number of cholinergic neurons mediate hyperaggression in female Drosophila. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2019 08 20; 116(34):17029-17038.<ref name=\":5\"/>\n* Palavicino-Maggio CB, Trannoy S, Holton KM, Song X, Li K, Nevo E. Aggression and courtship differences found in Drosophila melanogaster from two different microclimates at Evolution Canyon, Israel. Sci Rep. 2019 03 11; 9(1):4084.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|last2=Trannoy|first2=S\u00e9verine|last3=Holton|first3=Kristina M.|last4=Song|first4=Xiaoying|last5=Li|first5=Kexin|last6=Nevo|first6=Eviatar|date=03 11, 2019|title=Aggression and courtship differences found in Drosophila melanogaster from two different microclimates at Evolution Canyon, Israel|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30858499|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=9|issue=1|pages=4084|doi=10.1038/s41598-019-40701-8|issn=2045-2322|pmc=6411990|pmid=30858499}}</ref>\n* Palavicino-Maggio CB, Kuzhikandathil EV. Dietary Fructose and GLUT5 Transporter Activity Contribute to Antipsychotic-Induced Weight Gain. Schizophr Bull. 2016 09; 42(5):1270-9.<ref name=\":3\"/>\n* Effect of Clozapine on the Enteric System: Implications for Antipsychotic-Induced Weight Gain. Caroline B Palavicino-Maggio, Krishna Tobon, Veronique Douard, Ronaldo P. Ferraris, and Eldo V. Kuzhikandathil. The FASEB Journal 2011 25:1_supplement, lb390-lb390.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B|last2=Tobon|first2=Krishna|last3=Douard|first3=Veronique|last4=Ferraris|first4=Ronaldo P.|last5=Kuzhikandathil|first5=Eldo V.|date=2011-04-01|title=Effect of clozapine on the enteric system: implications for antipsychotic-induced weight gain|url=https://www.fasebj.org/doi/abs/10.1096/fasebj.25.1_supplement.lb390|journal=The FASEB Journal|volume=25|issue=1_supplement|pages=lb390\u2013lb390|doi=10.1096/fasebj.25.1_supplement.lb390|issn=0892-6638}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Caroline Palavicino-Maggio\n| image             = File:Caroline Palavicino-Maggio.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| caption           = \n| birth_date        = \n| birth_place       = Harlem, New York City\n| nationality       = Latin American\n| fields            = Neuroscience\n| workplaces        = Harvard Medical School\n| alma_mater        = B.S. Rider College, PhD New Jersey Medical School at Rutgers University, postdoctoral work Harvard Medical School\n| known_for         = Neural circuits underlying aggression in female Drosophila\n| awards            = 2016 Society for Translational and Academic Researcher Fellow, 2012 New York Academy of Sciences with PepsiCo. R&D Young Scientist Award, 2008 Alfred P. Sloan Foundation, Pre-doctoral Sloan Scholar, 2008 Rutgers University Honor Society for Research Scholars, 1998 Scholarship Recipient, Unilever Research, 1998   Eleanor Humanitarian Award\n| Institutions      = Harvard Medical School\n}}\n\n'''Caroline Palavicino-Maggio''' is a Latin American neuroscientist and Research Fellow in the Department of Neurobiology at [[Harvard Medical School]]. Palavicino-Maggio explores how gene expression in amine neurons and neural circuits leads to changes in social behavior, specifically aggression, in Drosophila. Palavicino-Maggio is committed to mentoring and inspiring first-generation students in STEM and serves as the Director of Outreach for the Journal of Emerging Investigators, an open-access journal  that publishes research conducted by middle and high school students as a means to expose young and underrepresented future scientists to academic research and the publishing process.\n\n== Early Life and Education ==\nPalavicino-Maggio was born in [[Harlem]] and grew up in [[Washington Heights, Manhattan|Washington Heights]] in [[New York City]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://brain.harvard.edu/hbi_humans/caroline-palavicino-maggio/|title=Caroline Palavicino-Maggio|website=Harvard Brain Science Initiative|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> Her mother was an immigrant from [[Colombia]] and her father was an immigrant from [[Chile]]. Later in her childhood, Palavicino-Maggio\u2019s family moved across the river to a small factory town in New Jersey called Edgewater where her mother worked in retail and her father worked as an elevator mechanic.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nPalavicino-Maggio was 13 years old, her sister ended her own life.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://storiesinscience.org/2020/03/10/humans-of-hbi-caroline-palavicino-maggio/|title=Humans of HBI: Caroline Palavicino-Maggio|date=2020-03-11|website=Stories in Science|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> This life-altering experience motivated Palavicino-Maggio to focus her career on neuroscience, specifically neurochemistry in the context of behavior.<ref name=\":1\" /> Further, Palavicino-Maggio experienced violent crimes in the various neighbourhoods she lived as a child, and this experience further motivated her to study the neurobiology of aggression as well as focus her work towards one day contributing to criminal psychology, law to effect change at the societal level.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nWith her drive to study neuroscience, Palavicino-Maggio attended [[Rider University|Rider College]] for her undergraduate education.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.emerginginvestigators.org/staff|title=Staff {{!}} Journal of Emerging Investigators|last=JEI|website=www.emerginginvestigators.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> She majored in biopsychology and political sociology<ref name=\":2\" /> becoming the first female in her family to pursue post-secondary education.<ref name=\":0\" /> Palavicino-Maggio graduated from Rider University in 2002 with a Bachelors of Science and then pursued research experience at both Rockefeller University and Columbia University as a research assistant\u00a0from 2002 to 2008.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://njms.rutgers.edu/departments/pharmacology/graduate_students.cfm|title=Rutgers New Jersey Medical School|website=njms.rutgers.edu|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> During this time, Palavicino-Maggio had the opportunity to present her research at the [[Society for Neuroscience]] conference, and on her way there sat next to Dr. Nick Ingolglia, the Associate Dean of [[New Jersey Medical School]] at [[Rutgers University]] and he inspired her to pursue graduate education.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2009, Palavicino-Maggio began her graduate degree at [[New Jersey Medical School|Rutgers University at New Jersey Medical School]] in the Department of Pharmacology and Physiology.<ref name=\":2\" /> Under the mentorship of Dr. Andrew Thomas and Dr. Eldo Kuzhikandathil, Palavicino-Maggio focused her graduate work in looking at the effects of neuropsychiatric drugs on weight gain.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|last2=Kuzhikandathil|first2=Eldo V.|date=09 2016|title=Dietary Fructose and GLUT5 Transporter Activity Contribute to Antipsychotic-Induced Weight Gain|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27056716|journal=Schizophrenia Bulletin|volume=42|issue=5|pages=1270\u20131279|doi=10.1093/schbul/sbw037|issn=1745-1701|pmc=4988743|pmid=27056716}}</ref> One of the many reasons that patients stop taking medication to treat mental illness is due to side effects like weight gain.<ref name=\":3\" /> Understanding how these side effects manifest as a means to find ways to alleviate them may help with patient compliance, health, and wellbeing.<ref name=\":3\" /> Palavicino-Maggio hypothesized that [[Antipsychotic|antipsychotics]] modulate [[fructose]] absorption in the intestine by affecting GLUT5 function, a transporter for fructose, and thus contributing to weight gain.<ref name=\":3\" /> \u00a0Palavicino-Maggio found that [[clozapine]], a typical antipsychotic, induced weight gain in mice and increased fructose uptake by the intestinal GLUT5 transporter though it did not increase expression of the transporter.<ref name=\":3\" /> They further found this transporter to be essential for antipsychotic induced weight gain.<ref name=\":3\" /> Interestingly, clozapine also seemed to slow blood glucose lowering and protein lipogenesis.<ref name=\":3\" /> \u00a0Palavicino-Maggio graduated with a PhD in Neuropharmacology and Neurophysiology in 2013 and her thesis was titled \"Effect of Antipsychotics on the Enteric Nervous System: Implications for Weight Gain\".<ref>{{Cite book|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Effect_of_Antipsychotics_on_the_Enteric.html?id=tARJngEACAAJ|title=Effect of Antipsychotics on the Enteric Nervous System: Implications for Weight Gain|date=2013|publisher=Palavicino-Maggio|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== Career and Research ==\nPalavicino-Maggio was eager to continue in academia and pursued her postdoctoral work at Harvard Medical School in 2016.<ref name=\":2\" /> Before starting in the lab, Palavicino-Maggio took a [[Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory]] course in [[Drosophila]] Neurobiology: Genes, Circuits and Behavior to prepare to work under the mentorship of Dr. Edward Kravitz at Harvard studying aggression in drosophila.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://meetings.cshl.edu/alumni.aspx?course=C-DROS&year=17|title=CSHL Meetings|website=meetings.cshl.edu|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n\nPalavicino-Maggio\u2019s work explores the function and cellular localization of proteins in ''Drosophila melanogaster'', fruit flies, that correlate to hyper-aggressive phenotypes.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hms.harvard.edu/bss/neuro/kravitz/people.html|title=People|website=www.hms.harvard.edu|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> By understanding the neural substrates for aggression in model organisms, Palavicino-Maggio\u2019s research sets the stage for a better understanding of how these genes drive aggressive behaviors and how they could be targeted therapeutically in patients with neuropsychiatric disorders.<ref name=\":4\" /> \n\nPalavicino-Maggio has explored patterns in aggressive behavior in two different species of Drosophila and found that Drosophila from cooler microclimates showed more aggression and more successful courtship behavior compared to the Drosophila from the warmer climate.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|last2=Trannoy|first2=S\u00e9verine|last3=Holton|first3=Kristina M.|last4=Song|first4=Xiaoying|last5=Li|first5=Kexin|last6=Nevo|first6=Eviatar|date=2019-03-11|title=Aggression and courtship differences found in Drosophila melanogaster from two different microclimates at Evolution Canyon, Israel|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-019-40701-8|journal=Scientific Reports|language=en|volume=9|issue=1|pages=1\u20139|doi=10.1038/s41598-019-40701-8|issn=2045-2322}}</ref> This research set the stage for Palavicino-Maggio to explore the biological basis of aggression, work that was published in the [[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences]] in 2019.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|last2=Chan|first2=Yick-Bun|last3=McKellar|first3=Claire|last4=Kravitz|first4=Edward A.|date=08 20, 2019|title=A small number of cholinergic neurons mediate hyperaggression in female Drosophila|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31391301|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=116|issue=34|pages=17029\u201317038|doi=10.1073/pnas.1907042116|issn=1091-6490|pmc=6708353|pmid=31391301}}</ref> Palavicino-Maggio and her team narrowed in on the question of which neural circuits govern aggression in female flies and if this circuit is important in the expression of aggressive behavior in male flies.<ref name=\":5\" /> While it is often thought that males are more aggressive than females in most species, Palavicino-Maggio and her colleagues saw quite the opposite when they screened for aggressive behaviors in fly lines using Drosophila Flylight Gal4.<ref name=\":5\" /> They found that the GMR26E01-Gal4 line had extremelty aggressive females, but males with normal aggressive behavior. <nowiki>https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31391301</nowiki>\u00a0 Further, the fights that the females engaged in, ended in hierarchical social relationships among the flies.<ref name=\":5\" /> They then tried to hone in on which subpopulation of neurons were responsible for driving this behavior and they found 2-4 pairs of neurons in the female brain pC1 region that were cholinergic and weakly GABAergic that seemed to drive the aggressive behavior in females but did not exist in males.<ref name=\":5\" /> The fascinating finding that such a small populations of neurons can drive specific and intense behavioral outputs will serve as a critical tool and model to understand how exactly interactions between neurons drive complex behaviors and provide a stepping stone for translation into more complex models of social behavior.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== Advocacy and Service ==\nPalavicino-Maggio is actively involved in promoting diversity, equity, and inclusion in her scientific community.<ref name=\":0\" /> Palavicino-Maggio\u00a0 is a board member of the Harvard Latino Alumni Association, the Outreach director of the Journal of Emerging Investigators, an appointed member of the multiple committees within in Harvard\u2019s Office for Diversity, Inclusion, and Community Partnership, and the Mentoring Director of the Health Professions Recruitment and Exposure Program at Harvard Medical School.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nJournal of Emerging Investigators, where Palavicino-Maggio holds the title Director of Outreach, is an open-access journal that publishes research conducted by middle and high school students as a means to expose young and underrepresented future scientists to academic research and the publishing process.<ref name=\":2\" /> As the Director of Outreach, Palavicino-Maggio helps to recruit submissions from students around the world, specifically Central America, South America, and Africa.<ref name=\":2\" /> One of the projects she has been working on with students from the Boston community focuses on exploring the prevalence of antibiotic resistant bacteria around Boston.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://emerginginvestigators.org/articles/investigation-of-everyday-locations-for-antibiotic-resistant-bacteria-in-cambridge-massachusetts|title=Investigation of Everyday Locations for Antibiotic-resistant Bacteria in Cambridge, Massachusetts {{!}} Journal of Emerging Investigators|website=emerginginvestigators.org|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> \u00a0Palavicino-Maggio and her students found that of all of the colonies they grew from water fountains, traffic lights, phones, sneakers, and the Harvard T-station, only the Harvard T-station showed signs of resistant bacteria as bacterial cultures grew in the presence of ampicillin.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nWithin the Office of Diversity, Inclusion, and Community Partnership at Harvard, Palavicino-Maggio is involved in the Diversity Pipeline of Community Engagement Committee as well as the Equity, Inclusion, and Social Justice Committee, both led by Dean Joan Reede.<ref name=\":2\" /> As a Mentoring Director for Health Professions Recruitment and Exposure Program at Harvard Medical School, Palavicino-Maggio helps to equip underrepresented high school students with the proper skill sets and knowledge to succeed in STEM fields, especially in the biosciences.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nPalavicino-Maggio is also engaged in diplomacy work to bridge community and scientific connections between American and Cuban Scientists.<ref name=\":4\" /> As a part of these efforts, Palavicino-Maggio was able to host Enrique Beldarrain Chaple, the Chief of Research Department, the National Information Center of Medical Sciences and Professor of Public Health and History of\u00a0 Medicine at the National School of Public Health in Havana, Cuba.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dicp.hms.harvard.edu/sites/default/files/files/2016/Calendar/Beldarrain-Enrique.pdf|title=The Epidemic Diseases in Cuba|last=|first=|date=|website=Harvard Medical School Office for Diversity Inclusion and Community Participation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 18th, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\n\n* 2016 Society for Translational and Academic Researcher Fellow, Harvard Medical School<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://connects.catalyst.harvard.edu/Profiles/display/Person/148931|title=Caroline Palavicino-Maggio {{!}} Harvard Catalyst Profiles {{!}} Harvard Catalyst|website=connects.catalyst.harvard.edu|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref>\n* 2012 New York Academy of Sciences with PepsiCo. R&D Young Scientist Award<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 2011 NIMH Independent Research Grant - Effects of Atypical Antipsychotics on Fructose Metabolism and Weight Gain<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 2008 Alfred P. Sloan Foundation, Pre-doctoral Sloan Scholar<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 2008 Rutgers University Honor Society for Research Scholars<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 1998 Scholarship Recipient, Unilever Research, U.S.<ref name=\":7\" />\n* 1998 Eleanor Humanitarian Award<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n== Publications ==\n\n* Palavicino-Maggio CB, Chan YB, McKellar C, Kravitz EA. A small number of cholinergic neurons mediate hyperaggression in female Drosophila. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2019 08 20; 116(34):17029-17038.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|last2=Chan|first2=Yick-Bun|last3=McKellar|first3=Claire|last4=Kravitz|first4=Edward A.|date=08 20, 2019|title=A small number of cholinergic neurons mediate hyperaggression in female Drosophila|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/31391301|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America|volume=116|issue=34|pages=17029\u201317038|doi=10.1073/pnas.1907042116|issn=1091-6490|pmc=6708353|pmid=31391301}}</ref>\n* Palavicino-Maggio CB, Trannoy S, Holton KM, Song X, Li K, Nevo E. Aggression and courtship differences found in Drosophila melanogaster from two different microclimates at Evolution Canyon, Israel. Sci Rep. 2019 03 11; 9(1):4084.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|last2=Trannoy|first2=S\u00e9verine|last3=Holton|first3=Kristina M.|last4=Song|first4=Xiaoying|last5=Li|first5=Kexin|last6=Nevo|first6=Eviatar|date=03 11, 2019|title=Aggression and courtship differences found in Drosophila melanogaster from two different microclimates at Evolution Canyon, Israel|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/30858499|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=9|issue=1|pages=4084|doi=10.1038/s41598-019-40701-8|issn=2045-2322|pmc=6411990|pmid=30858499}}</ref>\n* Palavicino-Maggio CB, Kuzhikandathil EV. Dietary Fructose and GLUT5 Transporter Activity Contribute to Antipsychotic-Induced Weight Gain. Schizophr Bull. 2016 09; 42(5):1270-9.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B.|last2=Kuzhikandathil|first2=Eldo V.|date=09 2016|title=Dietary Fructose and GLUT5 Transporter Activity Contribute to Antipsychotic-Induced Weight Gain|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/27056716|journal=Schizophrenia Bulletin|volume=42|issue=5|pages=1270\u20131279|doi=10.1093/schbul/sbw037|issn=1745-1701|pmc=4988743|pmid=27056716}}</ref>\n* Effect of Clozapine on the Enteric System: Implications for Antipsychotic-Induced Weight Gain. Caroline B Palavicino-Maggio, Krishna Tobon, Veronique Douard, Ronaldo P. Ferraris, and Eldo V. Kuzhikandathil. The FASEB Journal 2011 25:1_supplement, lb390-lb390.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Palavicino-Maggio|first=Caroline B|last2=Tobon|first2=Krishna|last3=Douard|first3=Veronique|last4=Ferraris|first4=Ronaldo P.|last5=Kuzhikandathil|first5=Eldo V.|date=2011-04-01|title=Effect of clozapine on the enteric system: implications for antipsychotic-induced weight gain|url=https://www.fasebj.org/doi/abs/10.1096/fasebj.25.1_supplement.lb390|journal=The FASEB Journal|volume=25|issue=1_supplement|pages=lb390\u2013lb390|doi=10.1096/fasebj.25.1_supplement.lb390|issn=0892-6638}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n", "name_user": "Dan Koehl", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up, addedorphan,uncategorisedtags,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (4)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caroline_Palavicino-Maggio"}
{"title_page": "Ford v Ferrari", "text_new": "{{redirect|Le Mans '66|the 1966 race|1966 24 Hours of Le Mans}}\n{{short description|2019 sports action drama film directed by James Mangold}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Ford v Ferrari\n| image          = Ford v. Ferrari (2019 film poster).png\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[James Mangold]]\n| producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Peter Chernin]]\n* [[Jenno Topping]]\n* James Mangold\n}}\n| writer         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jez Butterworth]]\n* [[John-Henry Butterworth]]\n* [[Jason Keller (playwright)|Jason Keller]]\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Matt Damon]]<!--per cast listing on website: https://www.foxmovies.com/movies/ford-v-ferrari -->\n* [[Christian Bale]]\n}}\n| music          = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Marco Beltrami]]\n* [[Buck Sanders]]\n}}\n| cinematography = [[Phedon Papamichael]]\n| editing        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Michael McCusker]]\n* Andrew Buckland\n}}\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Chernin Entertainment]]\n* [[TSG Entertainment]]\n* Turnpike Films\n}}\n| distributor    = [[20th Century Fox]]\n| released       = {{Film date|2019|8|30|[[Telluride Film Festival|Telluride]]|2019|11|15|United States}}\n| runtime        = 152 minutes<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.tiff.net/events/ford-v-ferrari |title=Ford v Ferrari |website=TIFF |accessdate=August 25, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723173756/https://www.tiff.net/events/ford-v-ferrari|archive-date=July 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| budget         = $97.6 million<ref name=\"BOM\"/>\n| gross          = $225.5 million<ref name=\"NUM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Ford-v-Ferrari-(2019)#tab=summary |title=Ford v Ferrari (2019) - Financial Information |website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]] |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191230202112/https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Ford-v-Ferrari-(2019)#tab=summary |archive-date=December 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"BOM\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl990348801/ |title=Ford v Ferrari (2019) |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191118055744/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/release/rl990348801/ |archive-date=November 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Ford v Ferrari''''' (titled '''''Le Mans '66''''' in some European territories)<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/ford-v-ferrari-trailer-watch-video-le-mans-66-christian-bale-matt-damon-a8941376.html |title=Ford v Ferrari trailer: Christian Bale and Matt Damon star in first clip from Le Mans '66 |last=Shepherd |first=Jack |date=June 3, 2019 |website=[[The Independent]] |accessdate=June 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608012707/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/ford-v-ferrari-trailer-watch-video-le-mans-66-christian-bale-matt-damon-a8941376.html |archive-date=June 8, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> is a 2019 American [[Sports film|sports]] [[Drama (film and television)|drama film]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmovie.com/movie/ford-v-ferrari-v716808|title=Ford vs. Ferrari (2019) - James Mangold|publisher=[[AllMovie]]}}</ref> directed by [[James Mangold]] and written by [[Jez Butterworth]], [[John-Henry Butterworth]], and [[Jason Keller (playwright)|Jason Keller]]. The film stars [[Matt Damon]] and [[Christian Bale]], with [[Jon Bernthal]], [[Caitriona Balfe]], [[Tracy Letts]], [[Josh Lucas]], [[Noah Jupe]], [[Remo Girone]], and [[Ray McKinnon (actor)|Ray McKinnon]] in supporting roles.\n\nThe plot follows a determined team of American engineers and designers, led by automotive designer [[Carroll Shelby]] and his British driver, [[Ken Miles]], who are dispatched by [[Henry Ford II]] and [[Lee Iacocca]] with the mission of building the [[Ford GT40]], a new racing car with the potential to finally defeat the perennially dominant [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari racing team]] at the [[1966 24 Hours of Le Mans]] race in France. In early stages of the film's production, [[Tom Cruise]] and [[Brad Pitt]] were cast in the starring roles, but those plans fell through. Mangold was then hired in February 2018, and Damon, Bale, and the rest of the cast joined that summer. Filming began in July 2018 in California and lasted a little over two months.\n\n''Ford v Ferrari'' had its world premiere at the [[Telluride Film Festival]] on August 30, 2019, and was theatrically released in the United States on November 15 by [[20th Century Fox]]. The film has grossed $225.5 million worldwide and received acclaim from critics, who lauded the performances (particularly Bale's and Damon's), Mangold's direction, the editing and the racing sequences. It was chosen by the [[National Board of Review Awards 2019#Top 10 Films|National Board of Review]] as one of the ten best films of the year, and at the [[92nd Academy Awards]] received four nominations, including [[Academy Award for Best Picture|Best Picture]], and won [[Academy Award for Best Film Editing|Best Film Editing]] and [[Academy Award for Best Sound Editing|Best Sound Editing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2020/film/news/2020-oscar-nominations-list-academy-awards-nominees-1203461985/|title=Oscar Nominations 2020: The Complete List|date=2020-01-13|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2020-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113151810/https://variety.com/2020/film/news/2020-oscar-nominations-list-academy-awards-nominees-1203461985/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> For his performance, Bale was nominated for the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Motion Picture Drama|Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Drama]] and the [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2020-golden-globes-nominations-full-list-1259626/item/best-motion-picture-musical-comedy-1259661|title=Best Motion Picture - Musical or Comedy - Golden Globes: Full List of Nominations|website=The Hollywood Reporter|language=en|access-date=December 9, 2019|date=December 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209142818/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/lists/2020-golden-globes-nominations-full-list-1259626/item/best-motion-picture-musical-comedy-1259661|archive-date=December 9, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/national-board-of-review-2019-winners-irishman-1202193897/ |title= National Board of Review 2019: 'The Irishman' Wins Best Film, Adam Sandler Named Best Actor |publisher= [[National Board of Review]] |date= December 3, 2019 |accessdate= December 3, 2019 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20191203194830/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/12/national-board-of-review-2019-winners-irishman-1202193897/ |archive-date= December 3, 2019 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nIn 1963, [[Ford Motor Company]] Vice President [[Lee Iacocca]] proposes to [[Henry Ford II]] to purchase the cash-strapped [[Ferrari]] as a means to boost their car sales by participating in the [[24 Hours of Le Mans]]. [[Enzo Ferrari]] however, uses Ford's offer to secure a more lucrative deal with [[Fiat S.p.A.|Fiat]] that allows him to retain complete ownership of [[Scuderia Ferrari]]. In rejecting the proposed deal with Ford, Ferrari also intentionally insults both Ford Motors and Henry Ford II. In response, a furious Ford orders his racing division to build a car to defeat Ferrari at Le Mans. For this task, Iacocca hires [[Carroll Shelby International|Shelby American]] owner [[Carroll Shelby]], a racing driver who won Le Mans in [[1959 24 Hours of Le Mans|1959]] but was forced to retire due to a heart condition. In turn, Shelby enlists the help of [[Ken Miles]], a hot-tempered British racer and struggling mechanic.\n\nShelby and Miles test the [[Ford GT40#Mk I|Ford GT40 Mk I]] prototype at [[Los Angeles International Airport]], working out all of its design flaws until it is race-ready. Seeing that Miles is not their ideal driver, Ford opts to send [[Phil Hill]] and [[Bruce McLaren]] to the [[1965 24 Hours of Le Mans]] instead. As predicted by Miles, none of the Fords finish the race. While Ford sees this as a humiliating defeat, Shelby explains to him that the GT40 instilled fear in Enzo Ferrari, as it reached 218&nbsp;mph on the [[Mulsanne Straight]] before it broke down. Shelby and Miles continue development on the [[Ford GT40#Mk II|GT40 Mk II]], but Miles is nearly killed when the car's brakes fail during testing. In 1966, Ford Senior Vice President Leo Beebe takes over the racing division, with the intent to continue the program without Miles, but Shelby gives Ford a ride in the car and wagers his own company to convince Ford to agree that if Miles wins the [[24 Hours of Daytona]], he will be allowed to race at Le Mans.\n\nShelby American enters Daytona, but Beebe has a second Ford entered with [[NASCAR]] team [[Holman-Moody]] supporting it. While the Holman-Moody team has quicker pit stops, Shelby has Miles push his car's limit to 7,000 [[Revolutions per minute|RPM]], and he wins the race.\n\nAt the [[1966 24 Hours of Le Mans]], Miles struggles with a faulty door during the first lap, but after team engineer [[Phil Remington]] fixes it with a mallet, Miles begins to set lap records while catching up to the Ferraris. While racing with Ferrari driver [[Lorenzo Bandini]] \u2013 piloting Ferrari's new prototype [[Ferrari P|330 P3]] \u2013 Miles experiences brake failure and has his brake system replaced during his pit stop. Enzo Ferrari protests the move, but Shelby convinces race officials that the replacement is legal. Miles and Bandini once again duel on the Mulsanne Straight until Bandini blows his engine, eliminating the Ferrari from the race. With three Ford teams in the top positions, Beebe orders Shelby to have Miles slow down for the other two Fords to catch up with him and provide the press with a three-car [[photo finish]]. Miles is initially against this decision, continuing to set new lap records near the end of the race, but decides to let Ford have their way on the final lap. Ultimately, McLaren is declared the winner on a technicality, but Miles is grateful to Shelby for giving him the opportunity to race at Le Mans.\n\nTwo months after Le Mans, while testing the [[Ford GT40#J-car|J-car]] at [[Riverside International Raceway]], Miles once again experiences brake failure and is killed in the resulting crash. Six months later, Shelby pays Miles' widow Mollie and son Peter a visit and gives Peter a wrench that Miles threw at him before winning an [[Sports Car Club of America|SCCA]] race at [[Willow Springs International Motorsports Park|Willow Springs]] in 1963.\n\nFord continued its winning streak at Le Mans in [[1967 24 Hours of Le Mans|1967]], [[1968 24 Hours of Le Mans|1968]], and [[1969 24 Hours of Le Mans|1969]]. Miles was posthumously inducted into the [[Motorsports Hall of Fame of America]] in 2001.\n\n== Cast ==\n\n* [[Matt Damon]] as [[Carroll Shelby]], American former race car driver, automotive designer, and builder\n* [[Christian Bale]] as [[Ken Miles]], British [[World War II]] veteran and professional race car driver\n* [[Jon Bernthal]] as [[Lee Iacocca]], vice president of [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]]\n* [[Caitriona Balfe]] as Mollie Miles, Miles' wife\n* [[Josh Lucas]] as Leo Beebe, senior executive vice president\n* [[Noah Jupe]] as Peter Miles, Miles's son\n* [[Tracy Letts]] as [[Henry Ford II]], the [[Chief executive officer|CEO]] of Ford and grandson of automotive pioneer [[Henry Ford]] \n* [[Remo Girone]] as [[Enzo Ferrari]], founder of [[Ferrari]] and its automobile racing team [[Scuderia Ferrari]].\n* [[Ray McKinnon (actor)|Ray McKinnon]] as [[Phil Remington]]\n* [[JJ Feild]] as [[Roy Lunn]], a Ford engineer involved in the GT40 program\n* [[Jack McMullen]] as Charlie Agapiou\n* [[Corrado Invernizzi]] as Franco Gozzi, [[Enzo Ferrari]]'s right-hand man\n* Joe Williamson as [[Donald N. Frey]], Chief Engineer of Ford\n* [[Ian Harding]] as Ford Executive - Ian\n* Christopher Darga as [[John Holman (NASCAR owner)|John Holman]]\n\n== Production ==\nA film based on the rivalry between [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]] and [[Ferrari]] for the dominance at the Le Mans endurance race had long been in works at [[20th Century Fox]]. Initially, it was going to star [[Tom Cruise]] and [[Brad Pitt]] from an original screenplay by [[Jason Keller (playwright)|Jason Keller]], but the project fell apart after writers [[Jez Butterworth]] and [[John-Henry Butterworth]] drafted a script and [[Joseph Kosinski]] was brought on to direct.<ref name=\"Brad Pitt\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/brad-pitt-courted-tom-cruises-666348 |title=Brad Pitt Courted to Join Tom Cruise in 'Go Like Hell' (Exclusive) |first=Borys |last=Kit |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 18, 2013 |accessdate=June 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404021439/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/brad-pitt-courted-tom-cruises-666348 |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2013/10/tom-cruise-joseph-kosinski-circle-go-like-hell-618902/ |title=Tom Cruise circles Go Like Hell |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |last=Fleming |first=Mike |date=October 23, 2013 |accessdate=June 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404044000/https://deadline.com/2013/10/tom-cruise-joseph-kosinski-circle-go-like-hell-618902/ |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/may/27/michael-mann-go-like-hell |title=Michael Mann set to steer racing thriller Go Like Hell |first=Ben |last=Child |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=May 27, 2011 |accessdate=June 6, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603211714/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/may/27/michael-mann-go-like-hell |archive-date=June 3, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, 2018, it was announced that [[James Mangold]] had been brought on board to direct the film based on the previous script by Jason Keller, Jez Butterworth and John-Henry Butterworth.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/james-mangold-next-film-ford-ferrari-logan-1202687686/ |title=James Mangold to Direct Ford vs. Ferrari Film as 'Logan' Follow-Up |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date= |accessdate=February 5, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180205224120/http://variety.com/2018/film/news/james-mangold-next-film-ford-ferrari-logan-1202687686/ |archive-date=February 5, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later, [[Caitriona Balfe]], [[Jon Bernthal]], and [[Noah Jupe]] joined the cast alongside [[Christian Bale]] and [[Matt Damon]] in the lead roles.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/outlander-a-quiet-place-stars-join-ford-ferrari-movie-1114517 |title='Outlander' Star Caitriona Balfe, 'Quiet Place' Breakout Noah Jupe Join Ford vs. Ferrari Movie |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date= |accessdate=May 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180524031659/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/outlander-a-quiet-place-stars-join-ford-ferrari-movie-1114517 |archive-date=May 24, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/jon-bernthal-lee-iacocca-ford-v-ferrari-matt-damon-christian-bale-james-mangold-the-punisher-1202408992/ |title=Jon Bernthal In Talks To Play Lee Iacocca In 'Ford V Ferrari' |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date= |accessdate=June 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180613001611/https://deadline.com/2018/06/jon-bernthal-lee-iacocca-ford-v-ferrari-matt-damon-christian-bale-james-mangold-the-punisher-1202408992/|archive-date=June 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In July 2018, [[Jack McMullen]] was cast in the film to play one of Miles's key British mechanics, and [[Tracy Letts]] also joined to play [[Henry Ford II]], along with Joe Williamson.<ref name=\"McMullenCast\">{{cite news |last1=Wiseman |first1=Andreas |title='Brotherhood' & 'The Souvenir' Actor Jack McMullen Joins James Mangold's Ford Vs Ferrari Pic |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/brotherhood-jack-mcmullen-james-mangold-ford-vs-ferarri-christian-bale-matt-damon-1202429807/ |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=July 20, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826150113/https://deadline.com/2018/07/brotherhood-jack-mcmullen-james-mangold-ford-vs-ferarri-christian-bale-matt-damon-1202429807/ |archive-date=August 26, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"LettsCast\">{{cite news |last1=Wiseman |first1=Andreas |title=Tracy Letts To Play Henry Ford II In James Mangold's Ford Vs. Ferrari Pic |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/tracy-letts-henry-ford-james-mangolds-ford-ferrari-christian-bale-matt-damon-1202431987/ |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=July 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723231752/https://deadline.com/2018/07/tracy-letts-henry-ford-james-mangolds-ford-ferrari-christian-bale-matt-damon-1202431987/ |archive-date=July 23, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"WilliamsonCast\">{{cite news |last1=Wiseman |first1=Andreas |title='Here And Now' Actor Joe Williamson Joins Fox's Ford Vs. Ferrari Pic, Signs With Abrams Artists Agency |url=https://deadline.com/2018/07/here-and-now-joe-williamson-ford-vs-ferrari-abrams-artists-agency-1202433069/ |accessdate=July 26, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=July 25, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726015109/https://deadline.com/2018/07/here-and-now-joe-williamson-ford-vs-ferrari-abrams-artists-agency-1202433069/ |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> In August 2018, [[JJ Feild]] was cast in the film to play the automotive engineer [[Roy Lunn]], the head of Ford Advanced vehicles in England and the right-hand man to [[Henry Ford II]].<ref name=\"FeildCast\">{{cite news |last1=N'Duka |first1=Amanda |title=James Mangold's Untitled Ford/Ferrari Pic Adds JJ Feild; Elizabeth Mitchell Joins 'Welcome to Pine Grove!' |url=https://deadline.com/2018/08/james-mangold-ford-ferrari-jj-feild-elizabeth-mitchell-welcome-to-pine-grove-1202439089/ |accessdate=August 3, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=August 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180809025742/https://deadline.com/2018/08/james-mangold-ford-ferrari-jj-feild-elizabeth-mitchell-welcome-to-pine-grove-1202439089/ |archive-date=August 9, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref> Composer [[Marco Beltrami]] confirmed in an interview that he would be scoring the film, Beltrami having previously worked with Mangold on ''[[3:10 to Yuma (2007 film)|3:10 to Yuma]]'', ''[[The Wolverine (film)|The Wolverine]]'' and ''[[Logan (film)|Logan]]''.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mavity |first1=Will |title=Interview With 'A Quiet Place' Composer, Marco Beltrami |url=https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/interview-with-a-quiet-place-composer-marco-beltrami |website=NextBestPicture |accessdate=January 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190404021439/https://www.nextbestpicture.com/latest/interview-with-a-quiet-place-composer-marco-beltrami |archive-date=April 4, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Marco Beltrami to Score James Mangold's 'Ford v. Ferrari' |url=http://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/01/11/marco-beltrami-to-score-james-mangolds-ford-v-ferrari/ |website=Film Music Reporter |accessdate=January 12, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190112150259/http://filmmusicreporter.com/2019/01/11/marco-beltrami-to-score-james-mangolds-ford-v-ferrari/ |archive-date=January 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFilming began on July 30, 2018, and lasted for 67 days, taking place in California; [[New Orleans]], Louisiana; [[Atlanta]]; [[Savannah, Georgia|Savannah]]; and [[Statesboro, Georgia|Statesboro]], Georgia, as well as [[Le Mans]], France.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Karthik Prasad |first1=R.A |title=Untitled Ford vs. Ferrari Movie Working Title, Filming Start Date, Location Revealed |url=https://pursuenews.com/untitled-ford-vs-ferrari-movie-working-title-filming-start-date-location-revealed/ |accessdate=July 24, 2018 |website=pursuenews.com |date=July 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180811163756/https://pursuenews.com/untitled-ford-vs-ferrari-movie-working-title-filming-start-date-location-revealed/ |archive-date=August 11, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=FilmCA>{{cite report |title=Film and Television Tax Credit Program Program 2.0 |url=http://film.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2.0-Website-Approved-Projects-List-Online-07.23.2018.pdf |publisher=[[California Film Commission]] |page=2 |accessdate=July 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004225824/http://film.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2.0-Website-Approved-Projects-List-Online-07.23.2018.pdf |archivedate=October 4, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Race scenes that appear in the film as [[Daytona International Speedway|Daytona]] were filmed at [[Auto Club Speedway]] in [[Fontana, California|Fontana]]; many other race scenes were filmed at a Honda test track (doubling for the [[Riverside International Raceway]]) in [[Mojave, California|Mojave Valley]] and at the Porsche Experience (for the [[Dearborn, Michigan|Dearborn]] test track) in [[Carson, California|Carson]]. A few scenes were filmed at tracks in Georgia. The Le Mans grandstands, pits, and garages were replicated at the [[Agua Dulce Airpark]] in [[Agua Dulce, California|Agua Dulce]]. The hangar area where the cars were developed (originally at LAX) were filmed at [[Ontario International Airport]] in [[Ontario, California|Ontario]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2019-11-18/how-agua-dulce-played-le-mans-in-ford-v-ferrari |title=In 'Ford v Ferrari', famed Le Mans racetrack came to life in Agua Dulce |first=Charles |last=Fleming |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 18, 2019 |access-date=November 30, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130125001/https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2019-11-18/how-agua-dulce-played-le-mans-in-ford-v-ferrari |archive-date=November 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Music==\n{{main|Ford v Ferrari (soundtrack)}}\n\n==Release==\n''Ford v Ferrari'' premiered at the [[Telluride Film Festival]] on August 30, 2019,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/telluride-film-festival-2019-lineup-ford-vs-ferrari-judy-full-list-of-movies-1202706577/ |title=Telluride Film Festival: 'Ford V Ferrari', 'Judy', 'Motherless Brooklyn', Weinstein-Inspired Drama 'The Assistant' Among Premieres Headed To 46th Edition \u2013 Full List |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |first=Pete |last=Hammond |date=August 29, 2019 |accessdate=August 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829155107/https://deadline.com/2019/08/telluride-film-festival-2019-lineup-ford-vs-ferrari-judy-full-list-of-movies-1202706577/|archive-date=August 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://telluridecms-production.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/guides/46th-TFF-program-guide-FINAL.pdf |title=Telluride Program Guide |accessdate=August 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829175338/http://telluridecms-production.s3.amazonaws.com/assets/guides/46th-TFF-program-guide-FINAL.pdf|archive-date=August 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and screened at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on September 9, 2019.<ref name=\"TIFF\">{{cite web |last1=Lang |first1=Brent |title=Toronto Film Festival: 'Joker', 'Ford v Ferrari', 'Hustlers' Among Big Premieres |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toronto-film-festival-joker-ford-v-ferrari-hustlers-lineup-1203275868/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=July 23, 2019 |date=July 23, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723140739/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/toronto-film-festival-joker-ford-v-ferrari-hustlers-lineup-1203275868/ |archive-date=July 23, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> It was subsequently released in the United States on November 15 by [[20th Century Fox]] in 2D, [[IMAX]], and [[Dolby Cinema]] formats.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/kingsman-prequel-moves-feb-2020-free-fall-lands-summer-release-1189367 |title='Kingsman' Prequel Moves to Next February, Ryan Reynolds' 'Free Guy' Lands Summer 2020 Release |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |first=Pamela |last=McClintock |date=February 23, 2019 |accessdate=February 23, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190224001126/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/kingsman-prequel-moves-feb-2020-free-fall-lands-summer-release-1189367|archive-date=February 24, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> It was previously scheduled to be released on June 28.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haring |first1=Bruce |title=20th Century Fox Sets Dates For Untitled James Mangold Ferrari Project, Kenneth Branagh's 'Death On The Nile' |url=https://deadline.com/2018/06/20th-century-fox-sets-dates-for-untitled-james-mangold-ferrari-project-kenneth-branaghs-death-on-the-nile-1202416198/ |accessdate=August 8, 2018 |website=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=June 23, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180813021250/https://deadline.com/2018/06/20th-century-fox-sets-dates-for-untitled-james-mangold-ferrari-project-kenneth-branaghs-death-on-the-nile-1202416198/ |archive-date=August 13, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe first trailer for the film debuted on June 2, 2019, during Game 2 of the [[2019 NBA Finals]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ford-v-ferrari-trailer-matt-damon-christian-bale-design-race-car-1214837 |title='Ford v. Ferrari' Trailer: Matt Damon, Christian Bale Team Up to Design Race Car |first=Katherine |last=Schaffstall |website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |accessdate=July 4, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712145737/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/ford-v-ferrari-trailer-matt-damon-christian-bale-design-race-car-1214837 |archive-date=July 12, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nShelby's 1967 memoir ''[[The Carroll Shelby Story]]'' was re-released on January 16, 2020 by Graymalkin Media for the opening of the film.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Carroll Shelby Story : Carroll Shelby : 9781631682872 |url=https://www.bookdepository.com/Carroll-Shelby-Story-Carroll-Shelby/9781631682872 |publisher=[[Book Depository]] |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Home media==\nThe film was released on digital format by [[20th Century Fox Home Entertainment]] on January 28, 2020, and on [[4K resolution|4K Ultra HD]] [[Blu-ray]] and [[DVD]] on February 11, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://collider.com/ford-v-ferrari-digital-bluray-details-release-date/ |title='Ford v Ferrari' Digital & Blu-ray Details, Release Date Revealed |first=Tom |last=Reimann |website=[[Collider (website)|Collider]] |date=January 8, 2020 |accessdate=January 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n{{As of|2020|3|7|df=US}}, ''Ford v Ferrari'' has grossed $117.6 million in the United States and Canada, and $107.9 million in other territories, for a worldwide total of $225.5 million.<ref name=\"BOM\" /> \n\nIn the United States and Canada, the film was released alongside ''[[Charlie's Angels (2019 film)|Charlie's Angels]]'' and ''[[The Good Liar]]'', and was projected to gross $23\u201330 million from 3,528 theaters in its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/ford-v-ferrari-charlies-angels-box-office-opening-preview-1202784822/ |title='Ford v Ferrari' To Do Donuts Around 'Charlie's Angels' With $50M Global Opening |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |last2=Tartaglione |first2=Nancy |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 13, 2019 |accessdate=November 13, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113172027/https://deadline.com/2019/11/ford-v-ferrari-charlies-angels-box-office-opening-preview-1202784822/ |archive-date=November 13, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It made $10.9 million on its first day, including $2.1 million from Thursday night previews. It went on to debut to $31.5 million, topping the box office.<ref name=opening>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/ford-v-ferrari-charlies-angels-weekend-box-office-1202787070/ |title='Ford v Ferrari' Cruising To $31M+, 'Charlie's Angels' Kicked Out Of Heaven With $8M+ Start |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 17, 2019 |accessdate=November 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191120184304/https://deadline.com/2019/11/ford-v-ferrari-charlies-angels-weekend-box-office-1202787070/ |archive-date=November 20, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> In its second weekend the film dropped 50% to $15.7 million, finishing second behind newcomer ''[[Frozen II]]'', and then made $16 million in its third weekend (including $19 million over the five-day Thanksgiving frame), finishing third.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/frozen-2-opening-weekend-box-office-tom-hanks-mister-rogers-movie-21-bridges-1202792831/|title='Frozen 2' Thaws Frigid B.O. Marketplace With $130M+, Smashing November Animated Pic Opening Records|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 24, 2019|accessdate=November 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191123133518/https://deadline.com/2019/11/frozen-2-opening-weekend-box-office-tom-hanks-mister-rogers-movie-21-bridges-1202792831/|archive-date=November 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/11/frozen-2-box-office-tuesday-november-record-knives-out-previews-thanksgiving-1202796248/ |title='Frozen 2' Hooks $126M+ Holiday Record, 'Knives Out' A $42M Win For Original Pics, 2019 YTD Crosses $10B+: Thanksgiving B.O. |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 1, 2019 |accessdate=December 2, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191201082951/https://deadline.com/2019/11/frozen-2-box-office-tuesday-november-record-knives-out-previews-thanksgiving-1202796248/ |archive-date=December 1, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It continued to hold well in the following weeks, making $6.7 million and $3.1 million in its fourth and fifth weekends.<ref>{{cite web|last=D'Alessandro|first=Anthony|title='Frozen 2' Leads Dreary December Weekend With $34M+, 'Playmobil' Plunges To $670K \u2013 Sunday Update|url=https://deadline.com/2019/12/frozen-2-already-past-300m-leading-dreary-december-weekend-with-40m-playmobil-coming-apart-1202802388/|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=December 8, 2019|date=December 8, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191207140806/https://deadline.com/2019/12/frozen-2-already-past-300m-leading-dreary-december-weekend-with-40m-playmobil-coming-apart-1202802388/|archive-date=December 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/2019W50/?ref_=bo_rl_table_1|title=Domestic 2019 Weekend 50|website=[[Box Office Mojo]]|accessdate=December 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191221000442/https://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/2019W50/?ref_=bo_rl_table_1|archive-date=December 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn review aggregation website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 92% based on 319 reviews, with an average rating of 7.75/10. The website's critics consensus reads: \"''Ford v Ferrari'' delivers all the polished auto action audiences will expect \u2013 and balances it with enough gripping human drama to satisfy non-racing enthusiasts.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ford_v_ferrari|title=Ford v Ferrari (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango Media]]|access-date=January 3, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190918055828/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/ford_v_ferrari|archive-date=September 18, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] assigned the film a weighted average score of 81 out of 100, based on 47 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/ford-v-ferrari|title=Ford v Ferrari Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=November 20, 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190902012348/https://www.metacritic.com/movie/ford-v-ferrari|archive-date=September 2, 2019}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a rare grade of \"A+\", while those at [[PostTrak]] gave it an overall positive score of 87% (with an average 4.5 out of 5 stars), with 68% saying they would definitely recommend it.<ref name=opening/>\n\nMick LaSalle of ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' gave the film a 4 out of 4 stars, saying that it \"is what it promises to be, a blast from the past\" and writing: \"''Ford v Ferrari'' could have just been a sports story, dramatizing an interesting chapter in racing, and it would have been fine. But in showing Ford and his minions' constant interference in the dedicated work of Miles and Shelby, this James Mangold film becomes a tale of souls battling the soulless.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/review-ford-v-ferrari-is-a-paean-to-masculinity-and-creativity| title=Review: 'Ford v Ferrari' is a paean to masculinity, and creativity| newspaper=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]| date=November 11, 2019| accessdate=November 25, 2019| first=Mick| last=LaSalle| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191113173837/https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/movies-tv/review-ford-v-ferrari-is-a-paean-to-masculinity-and-creativity| archive-date=November 13, 2019| url-status=live}}</ref> Eric Kohn of ''[[Indiewire]]'' gave the film a \"B\", saying that \"''Ford v Ferrari'' excels at evoking the sheer thrill of the race\u2014'a body moving through space and time', as one character says\u2014and it's compelling enough in those moments to make the case that nothing beats the thrill of competition.\"<ref>{{cite web |date=August 30, 2019 |author=Eric Kohn |title='Ford v Ferrari' Review: Matt Damon and Christian Bale Power Old-School Race Car Drama |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/ford-v-ferrari-review-matt-damon-christian-bale-1202170145/ |publisher=[[Penske Business Media]] |website=[[IndieWire]] |accessdate=August 30, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190831023526/https://www.indiewire.com/2019/08/ford-v-ferrari-review-matt-damon-christian-bale-1202170145/|archive-date=August 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]''{{'}}s Peter DeBruge praised the racing sequences and the performances of Bale and Damon, writing: \"The best sports movies aren't so much about the sport as they are the personalities, and these two go big with their performances.\"<ref>{{cite web |date=August 30, 2019 |last=DeBruge |first=Peter |title=Telluride Film Review: Christian Bale and Matt Damon in 'Ford v Ferrari' |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/ford-v-ferrari-review-1203319686/ |website=[[Variety (magazine)]] |accessdate=September 1, 2019|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190831164454/https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/ford-v-ferrari-review-1203319686/|archive-date= August 31, 2019|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"width:99%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" | Category